'[[Chic Harley Award]]'''\n:[[Paul Hornung]] \u2013 1956\n*'''[[Touchdown Club of Columbus#The Kellen Moore Award|The Kellen Moore Award]]'''\n:[[Rick Mirer]] \u2013 1992\n*'''[[Polynesian Player of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Ronnie Stanley]] \u2013 2015<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120915aab.html|title=Ronnie Stanley Named 2015 Polynesian College Football Player of the Year|date=December 8, 2015|publisher=University of Notre Dame|accessdate=December 16, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160109175056/http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120915aab.html|archive-date=January 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*'''[[Wuerffel Trophy]]'''\n:[[Drue Tranquill]] \u2013 2018<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wuerffeltrophy.org/wuerffel-trophy-winners|title=Wuerffel Trophy Winners|accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Coaching awards===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[Paul \"Bear\" Bryant Award]]'''\n:[[Ara Parseghian]] \u2013 1964<ref name=\"PBBA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheart.org/downloadable/heart/11950567165420708%20BB%20Previous%20Winners.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071202183725/http://www.americanheart.org/downloadable/heart/11950567165420708%20BB%20Previous%20Winners.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 2, 2007|accessdate=November 21, 2007|publisher=The American Heart Association|title=Paul \"Bear\" Bryant College Football Coaching Awards}}</ref>\n:[[Lou Holtz]] \u2013 1988<ref name=\"PBBA\" />\n*'''[[Eddie Robinson Coach of the Year]] Award'''\n:[[Ara Parseghian]] \u2013 1964<ref name=\"ERCotYA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sportswriters.net/fwaa/awards/robinson/index.html|title=Eddie Robinson Coach of the Year Award|publisher=Football Writers Association of America|accessdate=January 2, 2008}}</ref>\n:[[Lou Holtz]] \u2013 1988<ref name=\"ERCotYA\" />\n:[[Charlie Weis]] \u2013 2005<ref name=\"ERCotYA\" />\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/8745065/notre-dame-brian-kelly-wins-eddie-robinson-award|title=Notre Dame's Brian Kelly wins Eddie Robinson Award|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref>\n*'''[[The Home Depot Coach of the Year Award|Home Depot Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Tyrone Willingham]] \u2013 2002<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120902aab.html|title=Tyrone Willingham Named Home Depot National Coach of the Year|publisher=UND.cstv.com|date=December 9, 2002|accessdate=January 2, 2008}}</ref>\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012, 2018 <ref>{{cite news |title= Kelly named coach of the year |author= Ralph D. Russo|url= http://collegefootball.ap.org/article/notre-dames-kelly-wins-ap-coach-year-0|newspaper= Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette|date= December 5, 2012|accessdate= December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n*'''[[Walter Camp Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite news|title=Brian Kelly named Walter Camp Coach of the Year |author=Krausz, Tony |url=http://www.journalgazette.net/article/20121205/BLOGS02/121209759 |agency=Associated Press |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=December 19, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214132804/http://www.journalgazette.net/article/20121205/BLOGS02/121209759 |archivedate=December 14, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n{{col-2}}\n*'''[[Liberty Mutual Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://coachoftheyear.com/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020110230007/http://www.coachoftheyear.com/|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 10, 2002|title=Coach of the Year|work=coachoftheyear.com|accessdate=September 6, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n*'''[[Associated Press College Football Coach of the Year Award|Associated Press Coach of the Year Award]]'''\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite news |title= Notre Dame's Kelly wins AP coach of the year |author= Brady, James|url= http://chicago.sbnation.com/2013/1/3/3832052/brian-kelly-walter-camp-coach-of-the-year|publisher = SB Nation|date= January 3, 2013|accessdate= January 5, 2013}}</ref>\n*'''[[Sporting News College Football Coach of the Year|Sporting News Coach of the Year]]'''\n:[[Ara Parseghian]] \u2013 1966\n:[[Lou Holtz]] \u2013 1988\n:[[Brian Kelly (American football coach)|Brian Kelly]] \u2013 2012\n*'''[[George Munger Award]]'''\n:[[Tyrone Willingham]] \u2013 2002\n*'''[[Woody Hayes Trophy|The Woody Hayes Trophy]]'''\n:[[Lou Holtz]] \u2013 1988\n*'''[[Broyles Award]]'''\n:[[Bob Diaco]] \u2013 2012<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120412aaf.html|title=Bob Diaco Captures Broyles Award As Nation's Top Assistant Coach|publisher=UND.cstv.com|date=December 4, 2012|accessdate=December 4, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123215916/http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/120412aaf.html|archive-date=January 23, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Team awards===\n\n*'''[[Grantland Rice Trophy]]'''\n:[[Notre Dame Fighting Irish]] \u2013 1964, 1973, 1977, 1988 <ref name=\"sportswriters alltime\"/>\n\n*'''[[Joe Moore Award]]'''\n:[[Notre Dame Fighting Irish]] \u2013 2017 <ref name=\"joemooreaward.com\"/>\n\n===College Football Hall of Fame===\n{{see also|College Football Hall of Fame}}\nForty-six former Notre Dame players and 6 coaches have been inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]], located in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].<ref name=CFOB>{{cite web|url=https://footballfoundation.org/hof_search.aspx|title=Hall of Famers: Select 'Group by School'|accessdate=December 17, 2007}}</ref> Notre Dame leads all universities in players inducted.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Position\n!Year Inducted\n|-\n| [[Hunk Anderson]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1974\n|-\n| [[Angelo Bertelli]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1972\n|-\n| [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] ||2009\n|-\n| [[Ross Browner]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] ||1999\n|-\n| [[Jack Cannon (American football)|Jack Cannon]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1965\n|-\n| [[Frank Carideo]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1954\n|-\n| [[Dave Casper]] || [[Tight End|TE]] ||2012\n|-\n| [[George Connor (American football)|George Connor]] || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] ||1963\n|-\n| [[Bob Crable]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] ||2017\n|-\n| [[Jim Crowley]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1966\n|-\n| [[Zygmont Czarobski]] || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] ||1977\n|-\n| [[Dan Devine]] || Coach ||1985\n|-\n| [[Bob Dove]] || End ||2000\n|-\n| [[Ray Eichenlaub]] || [[Fullback (gridiron football)|FB]] ||1972\n|-\n| [[Bill Fischer (American football)|Bill Fischer]] || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]]/[[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1983\n|-\n| [[Tom Gatewood|Thom Gatewood]] || End || 2015\n|-\n| [[George Gipp]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1951\n|-\n| [[Jerry Groom]] || [[Center (American football)|C]] ||1994\n|-\n| [[Ralph Guglielmi]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||2001\n|-\n| [[Jesse Harper]] || Coach ||1994\n|-\n| [[Leon Hart]] || End ||1973\n|-\n| [[Frank \"Nordy\" Hoffman]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1978\n|-\n| [[Lou Holtz]] || Coach ||2008\n|-\n| [[Paul Hornung]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1985\n|-\n| [[John Huarte]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||2005\n|-\n| [[Raghib Ismail|Raghib \"Rocket\" Ismail]] || [[Wide receiver|KR/WR]] ||2019\n|-\n| [[Johnny Lattner]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1979\n|-\n| [[Elmer Layden]] || [[Fullback (gridiron football)|FB]] ||1951\n|-\n| [[Frank Leahy]] || Coach ||1970\n|-\n| [[Johnny Lujack]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1960\n|-\n| [[Jim Lynch]] || [[Linebacker|LB]] ||1992\n|-\n| [[Ken MacAfee]] || [[Tight End|TE]] ||1997\n|-\n| [[Jim Martin (American football)|Jim Martin]] || End/[[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] ||1995\n|-\n| [[Bert Metzger]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1982\n|-\n| [[Creighton Miller]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1976\n|-\n| [[Don Miller (football)|Don Miller]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1970\n|-\n| [[Edgar Miller]] || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] ||1966\n|-\n| [[Fred Miller (football b. 1906)|Fred Miller]] || [[Tackle (gridiron football position)|T]] ||1985\n|-\n| [[Wayne Millner]] || End ||1990\n|-\n| [[Alan Page]] || [[Defensive End|DE]] ||1993\n|-\n| [[Ara Parseghian]] || Coach ||1980\n|-\n| [[Knute Rockne]] || Coach ||1951\n|-\n| [[Louis Salmon]] || [[Fullback (gridiron football)|FB]] ||1971\n|-\n| [[Marchy Schwartz]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1974\n|-\n| [[William Shakespeare (football)|Bill Shakespeare]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]] ||1983\n|-\n| [[Emil Sitko|Emil \"Red\" Sitko]] || [[Halfback (American football)|HB]]/[[Fullback (gridiron football)|FB]] ||1984\n|-\n| [[John P. \"Clipper\" Smith|John \"Clipper\" Smith]] || [[Guard (American football)|G]] ||1975\n|-\n| [[Harry Stuhldreher]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1958\n|-\n| [[Joe Theismann]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||2003\n|-\n| [[Adam Walsh (football coach)|Adam Walsh]] || [[Center (American football)|C]] ||1968\n|-\n| [[Bob Williams (quarterback)|Bob Williams]] || [[Quarterback|QB]] ||1988\n|-\n| [[Tommy Yarr]] || [[Center (American football)|C]] ||1987\n|-\n| [[Chris Zorich]] || [[Defensive Tackle|DT]] ||2007\n|}\n\n==Uniforms==\n\n[[File:Notre Dame vs. Stanford (2006).jpg|thumb|240px|The team in their current home uniforms]]\nNotre Dame's home jersey is navy blue with white numerals, gold outlining, and a small interlocking \"ND\" logo on each sleeve. The away jersey is white with navy numerals, gold outlining, and the interlocking \"ND\" on the sleeves. In recent years, neither jersey included the player's name on the back, but names were included during the Dan Devine and Gerry Faust eras. However, for the Irish's [[Hawaii Bowl|Hawai'i Bowl]] appearance in 2008 vs. the [[Hawaii Warriors football|University of Hawai'i]], Notre Dame once again wore last names on their jerseys. Gold pants, with a small ND logo just below the left waist, are worn with both home and away jerseys.\n[[File:Maillots ND d\u00e9placement.jpg|thumb|left|100px|Former quarterback Brady Quinn in the current away uniform]]\nNotre Dame's helmets are solid gold with gray facemasks, the gold being emblematic of the University's famed \"Golden Dome.\"  Notre Dame's tradition for the team's student managers to spray-paint the team's helmets prior to each game ended in 2011 when the football equipment staff, along with Notre Dame Athletics Director Jack Swarbrick and head coach Brian Kelly outsourced the painting process to Hydro Graphics Inc.\n\nOver the years, Notre Dame has occasionally worn green instead of blue as its home jersey, sometimes adopting the jersey for an entire season \u2013 or more \u2013 at a time. Currently, Notre Dame reserves its green jerseys for \"special\" occasions. Often on such occasions, the Irish will take the field for warmups dressed in blue, only to switch to green when they go back to the locker room before kickoff. This tradition was started by Dan Devine in 1977 before the USC game. Notre Dame has also been known to switch jerseys at halftime, as during the 1985 USC game, and in the loss to [[Nile Kinnick]]-led [[Iowa Hawkeyes football|Iowa]] in 1939, although this was to help avoid confusion between their navy uniforms and Iowa's black ones. The current design of the jersey is kelly green with gold numbers and white outlining. For the 2006 Army game, Coach Charlie Weis broke out the Green jerseys as a reward to his senior players, as well finally ending the string of losses by the Irish when wearing green. Notre Dame wore throwback green jerseys in 2007 against USC in honor of the 30th anniversary of the 1977 National Championship team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/061107aab.html|title=Notre Dame Football Team to Wear Throwback Uniforms Against USC|work=cstv.com|accessdate=September 6, 2015}}</ref> On at least one occasion (1992 Sugar Bowl) Notre Dame has worn an away variant of the jersey: a white jersey with green numbers. Champion supplied football jerseys for The University of Notre Dame for over 50 years until they switched to Adidas in 2001. On July 1, 2014, the University of Notre Dame Athletic department will begin wearing uniforms and footwear supplied by Under Armour.\n[[File:Tyler Eifert.jpg|thumb|110px|Former tight end Tyler Eifert.]]\nDuring Gerry Faust's tenure (1981\u201385), Notre Dame's blue jerseys switched from the traditional navy to royal blue with gold and white stripes on the sleeves. The navy blue jerseys returned in 1984.\n\nNo uniform numbers have been retired by Notre Dame. Upon being issued a number, each player is given a card which lists some of the more famous players who have worn that particular number. Number 3 is perhaps the most famous number in Irish football history, having been worn by [[Ralph Guglielmi]], [[George Izo]], [[Daryle Lamonica]], [[Coley O'Brien]], [[Joe Montana]], Michael Floyd, [[Rick Mirer]] and [[Ron Powlus]], among others.<ref name=\"ND All-Time Roster\">{{cite web| url=http://www.und.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/nd/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/FBRecSuppAll-TimeRoster |title=ND Archives: All-Time Roster |publisher=und.cstv.com |accessdate=May 6, 2008}}</ref> Number 5 is also notable, as it is the only number to be worn by one of the Four Horsemen ([[Elmer Layden]]) a Heisman Trophy Winner ([[Paul Hornung]]) and a National Title winning Quarterback ([[Terry Hanratty]]).<ref name=\"ND All-Time Roster\"/> Number 7 has been worn by such Irish greats as 1964 Heisman Trophy winner John Huarte, 1970 Heisman runner-up Joe Theismann, Steve Beuerlein, Jimmy Clausen and Jarious Jackson.<ref name=\"ND All-Time Roster\"/>\n\nIn 2011, both Michigan and Notre Dame wore throwback uniforms in their game against each other. For the Shamrock Series games Notre Dame and their outfitters have announced that the school will wear specially-designed helmets, jerseys, and pants.\n\n==Facilities==\n\n===Notre Dame Stadium===\n[[File:Notredamestadiumgamedayband.jpg|thumb|right|320px|Notre Dame Stadium on game day, with student section and band]]\n{{main| Notre Dame Stadium}}\n\nNotre Dame Stadium is the home football stadium for the University of Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team. Located on the southeast part of the university's campus in Notre Dame, Indiana and with a [[seating capacity]] of 77,622, Notre Dame Stadium is one of the most renowned venues in college football.<ref name=\"capacity\" /> The ''[[Sporting News]]'' ranks Notre Dame Stadium as # 2 on its list of \"College Football Cathedrals\".<ref name=\"Sporting News Cathedrals\">{{cite web|url=https://www.msnbc.com/modules/sports/collegefootballstadiums/Default.asp?cp1=1|title=Sporting News College Football Cathedrals|work=MSNBC|accessdate=January 30, 2007 |archiveurl = http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20010912195116/http://msnbc.com/modules/sports/collegefootballstadiums/default.asp?cp1=1 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = September 12, 2001}}</ref> and the stadium experience evokes a more traditional feel. Notre Dame Stadium is used for football related activities and for Commencement (since 2010). Notre Dame Stadium had no permanent lighting until the expansion project in 1997. NBC paid for the lighting as they have televised all Notre Dame home football games since 1991. On April 12, 2014, it was announced during the annual Blue-Gold Spring Game that a FieldTurf synthetic surface would replace the grass field after the 2014 Commencement Weekend. In November 2014 the University of Notre Dame embarked on a $400&nbsp;million stadium expansion called the Crossroads Campus Project, which was completed in time for the 2017 season.\n\n===Cartier Field===\n{{main| Cartier Field}}\nCartier Field was the original playing field of the Fighting Irish. In 1930, it was replaced by Notre Dame Stadium, due to the growing popularity of ND football. Notre Dame's practice facility still bears the Cartier Field name. Most ND practices take place on Cartier Field.\n\n===Guglielmino Athletics Complex===\nKnown by fans as \"The Gug\" (pronounced \"goog\"), The Guglielmino Athletics Complex is Notre Dame's football headquarters. The Gug houses the offices for all team staff members, an auditorium, a weight room, a training room, the equipment room, the practice locker room, and various other spaces for the football team to utilize. The complex was underwritten by Don F. Guglielmino and his family.\n\n===Irish Athletic Center===\nThe indoor practice facility has a synthetic turf field and avideo board at midfield for replay and graphics. On the second level of the facility, there is a 1,600-square-foot recruiting lounge. In all, the facility totals 111,400 square feet, and the ceiling is 95 feet at its peak.\n\n==Rivalries==\n{{main|Notre Dame Fighting Irish football rivalries}}\n\n[[File:Jeweledshillelagh.jpg|thumb|250px|The First [[Jeweled Shillelagh]], awarded to the winner of the annual USC vs. Notre Dame game.]]\nNotre Dame has rivalries with several universities. Although the Fighting Irish competes as an Independent, they play a more national schedule and have frequently scheduled opponents. [[USC Trojans football|USC]], [[Michigan Wolverines football|Michigan]], [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State]], [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]], [[Pitt Panthers football|Pitt]], and [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]] are among Notre Dame's oldest rivals.\n\n===USC===\n{{main|Notre Dame\u2013USC football rivalry}}\nUSC is Notre Dame's primary rival. The rivalry has produced more national titles, Heisman trophies, and All-Americans than any other. It is considered one of the most important rivalries in college football,<ref name=greatest>{{cite web|url=http://cfn.scout.com/2/591649.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070309013228/http://cfn.scout.com/2/591649.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=March 9, 2007|title=The Ten Greatest College Football Rivalries|accessdate=April 24, 2008}}</ref> and is often called the greatest rivalry not dictated by [[List of college athletic conferences|conference]], affiliation, or [[geography]].<ref name=\"USCNDtheGreatest\">{{cite news |last=Walters |first=John |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/writers/john_walters/10/12/inside.cfb/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060509113608/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/writers/john_walters/10/12/inside.cfb/index.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 9, 2006 |title=Does it get any better than this? |work=si.com |date=October 13, 2005 |accessdate=April 24, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Other than during World War II, the teams have played each other since 1926. Notre Dame leads the series 46\u201336\u20135 through the conclusion of the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/notre-dame/vs/usc|title=Winsipedia - Notre Dame Fighting Irish vs. USC Trojans football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>{{disputed inline|date=November 2018}}\n\n===Navy===\n{{main|Navy\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry}}\nNavy and Notre Dame have one of the longest continuous series in college football, having played 83 games without interruption since 1927. Notre Dame had a 43-game win streak during this time frame, the longest in Division 1-A football, which ended in 2007.  Navy won three of four consecutive meetings in 2007, 2009, and 2010. Notre Dame has won in 2011, 2012, 2013, 2014 and 2015. Navy won in 2016. Notre Dame won in 2017.\n\n===Michigan===\n{{main|Michigan\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry}}\n{{POV section|date=November 2019}}\nMichigan is considered Notre Dame's first and oldest rivalry. The first meeting was a Michigan victory in 1887, followed by seven more Wolverine wins through 1908.  The two schools have long competed for the best all-time win percentage in the FBS, which Michigan leads again since 2016. Following Michigan's initial 8 victories, Notre Dame leads the series 17-16-1.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.si.com/college/2018/08/31/michigan-notre-dame-results-history-all-time-rivalry |title=Michigan vs. Notre Dame: All-Time Head-to-Head Rivalry Results |last=Jones |first=Kaelen |date=August 31, 2018 |website=https://www.si.com |publisher=Sports Illustrated |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> Since the resumption of the rivalry in 1943, Notre Dame has won 8 wire service poll national championships and Michigan has won 2.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/history/football/fbs|title=FBS Football Championship History &#124; NCAA.com|website=www.ncaa.com}}</ref>  The rivalry was also colored and intensified by the inimical relationship between each school's early 20th century coaches, both later CFB Hall of Fame members, Michigan's Fielding Yost and Notre Dame's Knute Rockne.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/7954463/hate-fueled-football-great-rivalries |title=Hate fueled one of the great rivalries |last=Maisel |first=Ivan |date=May 21, 2012 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=April 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis rivalry stopped after the 2014 season, during which Notre Dame shut out Michigan for the first time in the rivalry's history. Shortly before the 2012 game, the [[Associated Press]] reported that Notre Dame had exercised a three-year out clause in their series contract. This series was the first casualty of Notre Dame's  arrangement with the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]], under which the Fighting Irish must play five games per season against ACC opponents after the school joined the ACC in all sports except for football and hockey in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/8423552/notre-dame-fighting-irish-opts-series-michigan-wolverines |title=ND-Michigan to end after 2014 |first=Matt |last=Fortune |publisher=ESPN.com |date=September 26, 2012 |accessdate=September 30, 2012}}</ref> In 2016, Michigan announced that the rivalry would resume for two consecutive seasons, in 2018 and 2019. The Irish won the first of the two by a score of 24-17 while Michigan prevailed in the second 45-14. Michigan leads the series 25\u201317\u20131 through the 2019 season.<ref name=\"series\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.winsipedia.com/michigan/vs/notre-dame|title=Winsipedia - Michigan Wolverines vs. Notre Dame Fighting Irish football series history|website=Winsipedia}}</ref>\n\n===Michigan State===\n{{main|Michigan State\u2013Notre Dame football rivalry}}\nThe [[Michigan State Spartans football|Michigan State Spartans]] are one of Notre Dame's most important rivals with the two teams playing for the Megaphone Trophy. Notre Dame holds an all-time 48\u201328\u20131 series winning margin. The one tie was the [[1966 Notre Dame vs. Michigan State football game|Game of the Century]], one of the greatest college football games ever played.<ref>{{cite book | title = The Biggest Game of Them All: Notre Dame, Michigan State and the Fall of 1966 | author = Mike Celzic | isbn = 0-671-75817-9 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/biggestgameofthe0000celi }}</ref> The Spartans' 28 victories over Notre Dame are second-most of any school after USC. The Megaphone Trophy series record is 32\u201326\u20131 in favor of Notre Dame. Michigan State won the Megaphone Trophy in 2010 after beating the Irish 34\u201331 in East Lansing on an overtime fake field goal play known as \"Little Giants\".{{citation needed|date=August 2015}}<!-- No YouTube... it isn't a reliable source --> In 2011, the Irish reclaimed the trophy with a 31\u201313 victory in which they led all the way.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/irish-first-win-beat-no-15-spartans-31-231616481.html |title=Irish get first win, beat No. 15 Spartans 31\u201313 |author=Gano, Rick |date=September 17, 2011 |work= |agency= Associated Press}}</ref>\n\n==Gameday traditions==\n{{see also|Band of the Fighting Irish}}\n[[File:NDBandBondHall.png|thumb|240px|The band playing in a pre-game ceremony before a football game]]\nDue to its long and storied history, Notre Dame football boasts many traditions unique to Notre Dame. Some of these are:\n* The tradition of having 23.9 karat gold in the helmet paint continues, with the painting process provided by Hydro Graphics, Inc. and no longer by student managers. The gold particles that are used on the helmet were collected from the re-gilding on the Notre Dame dome in 2007.  During the 2011 season, however, a new helmet paint scheme was introduced; while retaining the basic gold helmet and grey facemask look, the \"new\" gold is much more reflective than the \"old\"; there have already been several variations of this new \"gold chrome\" look, including \"brick\" and \"fish-scale\" texturing.<ref name=\"50 yrs of CFB\" />\n*Formerly, prior to the start of the game, the team attended mass in semi-formal attire at the [[Basilica of the Sacred Heart, Indiana|Sacred Heart Basilica]]. At the conclusion of mass, fans formed a line that the team walked through from the chapel to the stadium.<ref name=\"2007 ND Guide Intro 1\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.und.com/auto_pdf/p_hotos/s_chools/nd/sports/m-footbl/auto_pdf/07fbguideintro1 |title = 2007 Notre Dame Media Guide: Introduction Part I (Page 10 \u2013 Football Weekend at ND) | publisher= und.cstv.com | accessdate=May 6, 2008}}</ref> However, in 2011 the team changed its movements prior the game, instead taking buses back to The Gug for final meetings.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uhnd.com/traditions/irish-traditions-notre-dame-player-walk/|title=Irish Traditions: Notre Dame Player Walk|website=UHND.com - Notre Dame Football, Basketball, & Recruiting}}</ref> In 2013, Mass was moved to Friday night; as a result, the walk now originates from the Gug.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.nd.edu/news/father-thesing-to-serve-as-football-team-chaplain/|title=Father Thesing to serve as Notre Dame football team chaplain|first=Marketing Communications: Web // University of Notre|last=Dame|website=Notre Dame News}}</ref> \n[[File:Notredamepostgamehelmetraise.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Team raising their helmets to the student section after a win (or loss)]]\n* Earlier on game day, the [[Band of the Fighting Irish]] trumpet section plays [[Notre Dame, Our Mother]] & [[Victory March (fight song)|the Notre Dame victory march]] under the [[University of Notre Dame#Buildings and architecture|Golden Dome]], with visitors standing at the bottom of the [[Rotunda (architecture)|rotunda]], and behind the band members on each upper floor.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbnation.com/ad/18069400/notre-dame-band-trumpets-under-the-dome-football |title=How America\u2019s oldest college band preps for game day |publisher=Vox Media |website=SB Nation |date=8 Nov 2018 |access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*Coming out of the locker room, players slap the famous \"Play Like a Champion Today\" sign.\n* Prior to the start of the game, with around 15\u201330 seconds left on the pregame clock, a clip of [[Cathy Richardson]] singing \"Here Come The Irish\" is played, followed up by [[I'm Shipping Up To Boston]], which continues to play until the football is [[Kickoff (gridiron football)|kicked off]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://slapthesign.com/2019/06/29/notre-dame-footballs-fan-experience-best-college-football/ |title=Notre Dame Football\u2019s fan experience is the best in college football |first=Ben |last=Belden |publisher=FanSided |website=Slap The Sign |date=29 June 2019 |access-date=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n*Between the third and fourth quarters of home games, the Notre Dame Marching Band plays the finale to the [[1812 Overture]], as the crowd reacts with synchronized waving of arms, with their fingers in the shape of a \"K\" for Kelly. (\"W\" for both Weis and Willingham and \"L\" for Lou Holtz)\n*Since 1960, Sergeant Tim McCarthy for the Indiana State Police has read out a driving safety announcement to the crowd during the fourth quarter. When Sergeant McCarthy begins his announcement, the crowd goes silent to hear his message, which invariably ends with a pun.<ref name=\"McCarthy\">{{cite web |last=Katzmann |first=Kristy |url=http://www.nd.edu/~ndmag/copau00.htm |title=Tim McCarthy adds puns to football announcements:Football announcer punches it up |publisher=Notre Dame Magazine |date=Fall 2000 |accessdate=July 19, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725135310/http://www.nd.edu/~ndmag/copau00.htm |archivedate=July 25, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Sergeant McCarthy retired from this duty in the 2015 season after 55 years of fan-favorite messages. He was honored on the field on September 26, 2015, to deliver his last in-person address, in which he repeated the same announcement he did on his first gameday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/092315aac.html|title=Tim McCarthy to Deliver One Final Live Safety Message At Notre Dame-Massachusetts Football Game Saturday|website=Und.com|accessdate=November 16, 2017}}</ref>\n*At the conclusion of every home game, the team turns to the student section to salute them by raising their helmets in the air. They do this after a win or after a loss.<ref name=\"2007 ND Guide Intro 1\" /> Then, the band plays the Alma Mater, \"Notre Dame, Our Mother\". Those who stay link arms and sing the lyrics.\n\n==Irish in the NFL==\n{| class=\"infobox bordered\" style=\"width: 22em; text-align: left;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: larger;\" |\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Notre Dame Fighting Irish}}; text-align:center;\"|Irish in the NFL\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Notre Dame Fighting Irish}}; text-align:center;\"|NFL Draft Selections<ref name=\"2012 Notre Dame Football Media Guide\"/><ref name=\"Irish NFL Draft History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.drafthistory.com/n_college/college_n.html | title=Notre Dame NFL Draft History by numbers | work=drafthistory.com | accessdate = July 16, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | Total selected:\n| align=center|495\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | First picks in draft:\n| align=center|5\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | 1st Round:\n| align=center|65\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Notre Dame Fighting Irish}}; text-align:center;\"| NFL Achievements<ref name=\"Irish in Superbowl\"/>\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | In the [[Super Bowl]]:\n| align=center|49\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | Won the [[Super Bowl]]:\n| align=center|40\n|-\n! style=\"padding-left:0.5em\" | [[Pro Football Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]]rs:\n| align=center|13\n|}\nSince the NFL began drafting players in 1936, 495 Notre Dame football players have been selected by NFL teams. Additionally, Notre Dame has had 65 players selected in the first round of the NFL draft, including five overall number one picks. Of the 46 Super Bowls competed, only 14 teams have won the event without an Irish player on the roster.<ref name=\"Irish in Superbowl\">{{cite news|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020612aaa.html|title=Justin Tuck Stars in Super Bowl Again As Giants Top Patriots For Second Time in Four Years|publisher=UND.cstv.com|date=February 6, 2012|accessdate=August 26, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121119010853/http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/020612aaa.html|archive-date=November 19, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Looking at both participating team rosters, there have only been five Super Bowls that did not feature at least one former Notre Dame player on either team's roster \u2013 Denver vs. Atlanta, 1999; Dallas vs. Buffalo, 1994; Washington vs. Denver, 1988; Dallas vs. Denver, 1978; and Baltimore vs. Dallas, 1971.<ref name=\"Irish in Superbowl\"/> Eleven former players have won multiple Super Bowls: Mark Bavaro, Rocky Bleier, Nick Buoniconti, Eric Dorsey, Dave Duerson, David Givens, Terry Hanratty, Bob Kuechenberg, Joe Montana, Steve Sylvester and Justin Tuck.<ref name=\"Irish in Superbowl\"/>\n\n===Pro Football Hall of Fame===\nThirteen former Notre Dame players/alumni have been inducted into the [[Pro Football Hall of Fame]], ranking it 1st of all College Football Programs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/notre-dame-now-ranks-first-in-most-pro-football-hall-of-famers-020716| title= Hall of Famers by College| work=profootballhof.com | accessdate=April 23, 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080418093119/http://www.profootballhof.com/hof/colleges.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = April 18, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Irish NFL HOF\">{{cite web |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/01/31/notre-dame-catches-usc-in-pro-football-hall-of-famers/| title= Notre Dame catches USC in Pro Football Hall of Famers|work=collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com | accessdate=February 1, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n*1963: [[Curly Lambeau]] \u2013 [[Green Bay Packers]] 1919\u201349\n*1963: [[John McNally (American football)|John McNally]]* \u2013 [[Milwaukee Badgers]] 1925\u20131926, [[Duluth Eskimos]] 1926\u20131927, [[Pottsville Maroons]] 1928, Green Bay Packers 1929\u20131933, 1935\u20131936, [[Pittsburgh Steelers|Pittsburgh Pirates]] (Steelers) 1934, 1937\u20131938\n*1964: [[George Trafton]] \u2013 [[Chicago Bears]] 1920\u201332\n*1968: [[Wayne Millner]] \u2013 Boston and [[Washington Redskins]] 1936\u201341, 1945\n*1975: [[George Connor (American football)|George Connor]] \u2013 Chicago Bears 1948\u201355\n*1986: [[Paul Hornung]] \u2013 Green Bay Packers 1957\u201362, 1964\u201366\n*1988: [[Alan Page]] \u2013 [[Minnesota Vikings]] 1967\u201378, Chicago Bears 1978\u201381\n*2000: [[Joe Montana]] \u2013 [[San Francisco 49ers]] 1979\u201392, Kansas City Chiefs 1993\u201394\n*2001: [[Nick Buoniconti]] \u2013 [[Boston Patriots]] 1962\u201368, [[Miami Dolphins]] 1969\u201374, 1976\n*2002: [[Dave Casper]] \u2013 [[Oakland Raiders]] 1974\u201380, [[Houston Oilers]] 1980\u201383, Minnesota Vikings 1983\n*2015: [[Jerome Bettis]] \u2013 [[St. Louis Rams|Los Angeles/St. Louis Rams]] ([[1993 NFL season|1993]]\u2013[[1995 NFL season|1995]]), [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] ([[1996 NFL season|1996]]\u2013[[2005 NFL season|2005]])\n*2015: [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]] \u2013 [[Oakland Raiders|Los Angeles/Oakland Raiders]] ([[1988 NFL season|1988]]\u2013[[2003 NFL season|2003]]), [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] ([[2004 NFL season|2004]])\n*2016: [[Edward J. DeBartolo Jr.]] \u2013 Former San Francisco 49ers Owner, received B.A. from Notre Dame, inducted into Pro Hall of Fame in 2016 as a Contributor.\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>McNally graduated from St. John's (MN), but started his career at Notre Dame and is listed as a hall of famer under both schools in the Pro Football Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.profootballhof.com/players/john-blood-mcnally/| title= John (Blood) McNally| work=profootballhof.com | accessdate=April 23, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Current NFL players===\nAs of April 20, 2019.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Year Debuted !! Position !! Team\n|-\n| [[Josh Adams (American football)|Josh Adams]]\n| 2018 || [[Running Back|RB]] || [[New York Jets]]\n|-\n| [[Sheldon Day]]\n| 2016 || [[Defensive Tackle|DT]] || [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| [[Tyler Eifert]]\n| 2013 || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n|-\n| [[Matthias Farley]]\n| 2016 || [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || [[Indianapolis Colts]]\n|-\n| [[Will Fuller]]\n| 2016 || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| [[T. J. Jones]]\n| 2012 || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| [[J. J. Jansen]]\n| 2008 || [[Long Snapper|LS]] || [[Carolina Panthers]]\n|-\n| [[Deshone Kizer]]\n| 2017 || [[Quarterback|QB]] || [[Oakland Raiders]]\n|-\n| [[Ben Koyack]]\n| 2015 || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[Jacksonville Jaguars]]\n|-\n| [[Nick Martin (American football)|Nick Martin]]\n| 2016 || [[Center (gridiron football)|C]] || [[Houston Texans]]\n|-\n| [[Zack Martin]]\n| 2014 || [[Offensive Guard|OG]] || [[Dallas Cowboys]] \n|-\n| [[Troy Niklas]] \n| 2014 || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[New England Patriots]] \n|-\n| [[Romeo Okwara]] \n| 2016 || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[New York Giants]] \n|-\n| [[James Onwualu]]\n| 2017 || [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Los Angeles Chargers]]\n|-\n| [[C. J. Prosise]]\n| 2016 || [[Running Back|RB]] || [[Seattle Seahawks]]\n|-\n| [[Theo Riddick]] \n| 2013 || [[Running Back|RB]] || [[Detroit Lions]]\n|-\n| [[Kyle Rudolph]]\n| 2011 || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n|-\n| [[KeiVarae Russell]]\n| 2016 || [[Cornerback|CB]] || [[Cincinnati Bengals]]\n|-\n| [[Harrison Smith (American football)|Harrison Smith]]\n| 2012 || [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n|-\n|  [[Jaylon Smith]]\n| 2016 || [[Outside Linebacker|OLB]] || [[Dallas Cowboys]]\n|-\n| [[Ronnie Stanley]]\n| 2016 || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]] || [[Baltimore Ravens]]\n|-\n| [[John Sullivan (center)|John Sullivan]]\n| 2008 || [[Center (American football)|C]] || [[Los Angeles Rams]]\n|-\n| [[Golden Tate]]\n| 2010 || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[New York Giants]]\n|-\n| [[Manti Te'o]]\n| 2013 || [[Linebacker|LB]] ||[[New Orleans Saints]]\n|-\n| [[Stephon Tuitt]]\n| 2014 || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[Pittsburgh Steelers]]\n|-\n| [[Sam Young (American football)|Sam Young]]\n| 2010 || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]] || [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|-\n| [[Quenton Nelson]]\n| 2018 || [[Offensive Guard|OG]] || [[Indianapolis Colts]]\n|-\n| [[Mike McGlinchey (offensive lineman)|Mike McGlinchey]]\n| 2018 || [[Offensive Tackle|OT]] || [[San Francisco 49ers]]\n|-\n| [[Durham Smythe]]\n| 2018 || [[Tight End|TE]] || [[Miami Dolphins]]\n|-\n| [[Equanimeous St. Brown]]\n| 2018 || [[Wide Receiver|WR]] || [[Green Bay Packers]]\n|-\n| Nyles Morgan\n| 2018 || [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| Andrew Trumbetti\n| 2018 || [[Defensive End|DE]] || [[Chicago Bears]]\n|-\n| Greer Martini\n| 2018 || [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Minnesota Vikings]]\n|}\n\n==Media==\nThe Fighting Irish are unique among sports teams in the United States, as they are the only team, professional or college, to have all their games broadcast nationally on the radio, as well as the only team to have all of their home games broadcast nationally on television.<ref>{{cite web|title=Air Force Football Travels to Notre Dame|url=http://www.goairforcefalcons.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/100311aae.html|website=goairforcefalcons.com|accessdate=April 20, 2015}}</ref> Notre Dame famously left the [[College Football Association]], a consortium that administered television broadcast rights on behalf of over 64 schools, in 1990, in order to establish its own broadcasting deal with [[NBC]]. From 1968 to 2007, [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]] served as the official radio partner for the Irish, broadcasting their games for 40 consecutive years.<ref name=\"rejoin-irish\"/>\n\nUntil the 2006 Air Force game, Notre Dame had a record 169 consecutive games broadcast nationally on either NBC, ABC, ESPN, or [[CBS]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15593455/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070428031855/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15593455/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 28, 2007 |title=N.D.-Air Force not on major network \u2013 Notre Dame Central \u2013 MSNBC.com |publisher=MSNBC |date= |accessdate= |df=mdy-all }}</ref> The 2006 ND vs. Air Force game was broadcast on [[CBS Sports Network|CSTV]], a college sports channel owned by CBS who had an exclusive contract with the [[Mountain West Conference]], of which Air Force is a member.\n\n===Television===\n{{Main|Notre Dame Football on NBC}}\nNBC has been televising Notre Dame Home football games since the 1991 season.<ref name=\"1991 NBC Deal\" /> Notre Dame is the only [[NCAA Division I#Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] football team to have all of its home games televised exclusively by one television network. In addition to TV broadcasts, NBC also maintains several dedicated websites to ND football, and Notre Dame Central,<ref name=\"ND Central\">{{cite web |url=http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/25889627/ns/sports-notre_dame_central/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100916195630/http://nbcsports.msnbc.com/id/25889627/ns/sports-notre_dame_central/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 16, 2010 |title=MSNBC \u2013 Notre Dame Central \u2013 Stay Current with Notre Dame Football Scores, Schedule, Match-ups & Breaking News \u2013 MSNBC.com Front Page |publisher=Nbcsports.msnbc.com |date= |accessdate= |df=mdy-all }}</ref> which provides complete coverage, full game replays and commentary of the Notre Dame team. NBC's television contract with Notre Dame was renewed in April 2013 and is set to continue through the 2025 football season.<ref name=\"NBC2025\">{{cite web|last=Arnold|first=Keith|title=Notre Dame and NBC Sports renew partnership|url=http://irish.nbcsports.com/2013/04/17/offensive-line-rotation-coming-into-focus/#/2013/04/18/notre-dame-nbc-sports-renew-partnership/|publisher=nbcsports.com|accessdate=April 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Current broadcast team====\n*[[Mike Tirico]] ([[play-by-play]])\n*[[Doug Flutie]] ([[color commentator]])\n*[[Kathryn Tappen]] ([[sideline reporter]])\n\n===Radio===\nRadio rights to the Fighting Irish are currently held by [[IMG Sports]], who began a 10-year deal with the team in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title= Notre Dame And ISP Join To Produce Football Radio Network |publisher=und.cstv.com |url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/022208aaa.html |accessdate=April 21, 2008}}</ref> The new deal displaced its previous broadcast partner, [[Westwood One (1976\u20132011)|Westwood One]], who had broadcast Notre Dame football nationally on radio for 40 consecutive years (after taking over from the [[Mutual Radio Network]]). Notre Dame ended its relationship with Westwood One at the conclusion of the 2007 football season citing financial reasons.<ref name=\"rejoin-irish\">{{cite news |url=http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-070627greenstein,1,5244401.column?coll=cs-home-utility|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120707123345/http://chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports/columnists/cs-070627greenstein,1,5244401.column?coll=cs-home-utility|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 7, 2012|title=If Roberts has anything to say, he'll rejoin Irish|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=June 28, 2007}}</ref>\n\nIMG claims that the Notre Dame football broadcasts are carried by more affiliate stations than any other team (professional or collegiate, and in 'any' sport) in North America. The game broadcasts are also carried on [[Sirius XM Satellite Radio|SiriusXM's]] satellite radio and internet streaming services (on the Catholic Channel; two Catholic Channel hosts also produced a live broadcast from the official tailgate party prior to the 2017 USC game).<ref>{{cite news|title= I Get Caught in a Web of Lies! |publisher=jenniferfulwiler.com |url=http://jenniferfulwiler.com/2017/11/jennifer-fulwiler-show-highlights-for-week-ending-102717/ |accessdate=November 30, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Current broadcast team====\n*[[Paul Burmeister]] (play-by-play) 2018\u2013present\n*[[Ryan Harris (American football)|Ryan Harris]] (color commentator) 2018\u2013present\n\n====Former commentators====\n*[[Tony Roberts (sportscaster)|Tony Roberts]] (play-by-play) \u2013 1980\u20132005\n*Tom Pagna (color analyst)\n*[[Pat Haden]]\n*[[Ralph Guglielmi]]\n*[[Lindsey Nelson]]\n*[[Al Wester]][http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/090509aaf.html?wappref=std 1]\n*[[Don Criqui]] (play-by-play) \u2013 1974\u20131976, 2006\u20132017\n*[[Allen Pinkett]] (color analyst) 2002-2017\n*[[Tom Hammond]]\n*[[Mike Mayock]]\n\n==Future Schedules==\nAlthough the Notre Dame football program is not a full member of the [[Atlantic Coast Conference]] (ACC), it has an agreement to play an average of five ACC schools per season.  In return Notre Dame has access to the non-College Football Playoff ACC bowl line-up.<ref name=\"ACCmove\">{{cite web|last=Schwab|first=Frank|title=Notre Dame to the ACC, football not included... but football will have ACC feel to it|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/ncaaf-dr-saturday/notre-dame-acc-football-not-included-football-acc-141820042--ncaaf.html|publisher=Yahoo! sports|accessdate=September 28, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"ACC2014\">{{cite web|last=Hansen|first=Eric|title=Swarbrick offers updates on hot topics|url=http://articles.southbendtribune.com/2012-10-10/sports/34369074_1_football-series-shamrock-series-notre-dame-stadium|publisher=South Bend Tribune|accessdate=November 8, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130416004347/http://articles.southbendtribune.com/2012-10-10/sports/34369074_1_football-series-shamrock-series-notre-dame-stadium|archive-date=April 16, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Notre Dame currently utilizes a format of six home games in South Bend, five away games, and one major metropolitan area neutral site \"Shamrock Series\" home game for scheduling.<ref name=\"shamrock\">{{cite news |last=Hamilton|first=Brian |title=With Chicago next, Notre Dame 'Shamrock Series' games here to stay|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-08-16/sports/chi-with-chicago-next-notre-dame-shamrock-series-games-here-to-stay-20120816_1_miami-at-soldier-field-tyler-eifert-football-uniforms|publisher=ChicagoTribune.com|accessdate=October 11, 2012|date=August 16, 2012}}</ref> This includes preserving traditional yearly rivalries with [[USC Trojans football|USC]], [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]], and [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy]],<ref name=\"future\">{{cite news |last=Lazerus |first=Mark |title=Notre Dame drops Michigan from football schedule |url=http://www.suntimes.com/sports/colleges/15375852-419/notre-dame-drops-michigan-from-football-schedule.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005024543/http://www.suntimes.com/sports/colleges/15375852-419/notre-dame-drops-michigan-from-football-schedule.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |newspaper=suntimes.com |accessdate=November 16, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> five rotating ACC opponents (two away ACC games will coincide in even years with away games at Navy and three away ACC games will coincide in odd years with home games against Navy),<ref name=\"Joseph\">{{cite news|last=Joseph|first=Allen|title=Observer Exclusive: Swarbrick discusses eventful fall semester|url=http://www.ndsmcobserver.com/sports/observer-exclusive-swarbrick-discusses-eventful-fall-semester-1.2969241|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121231135510/http://www.ndsmcobserver.com/sports/observer-exclusive-swarbrick-discusses-eventful-fall-semester-1.2969241|url-status=dead|archive-date=December 31, 2012|accessdate=December 28, 2012|newspaper=The Observer|df=mdy-all}}</ref> two home and home series (one home game and one away game), one one-time opponent home game, and the traveling \"Shamrock Series\" home game.<ref name=\"JS\">{{cite web|title=Jack Swarbrick Press Conference Transcript \u2013 Notre Dame Announces 2014\u20132016 Schedules|url=http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/122013aad.html|publisher=und.com|accessdate=December 26, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140127060936/http://www.und.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/122013aad.html|archive-date=January 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"141516schedules\">{{cite web|title=Irish Release Football Schedules Through 2016|url=https://gameday.nd.edu/news/45259-notre-dame-announces-2014-2015-2016-football-schedules/|publisher=nd.edu|accessdate=December 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2020===\n{{CFB schedule\n| poll = AP\n| timezone = Eastern\n\n|{{CFB schedule entry\n| date = August 29\n| time = 2:00\n| w/l = \n| away