)|Brian Kelly]] || 10 || 67\u201336 || {{winpct|67|36}}  <!-- through Nov 11, 2019 --> <!-- https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/coaches/brian-kelly-2.html counts one additional loss; Discrepancy is unclear -->\n|}\n\u2020 George O'Leary did not coach a single practice or game, resigning five days after being hired for misrepresenting his academic credentials.<br />\n\u2021 Kent Baer served as interim head coach for one game at the 2004 [[Insight Bowl]] after Tyrone Willingham was fired.\n\n===Bowl games===\nNotre Dame has made 37 bowl game appearances, winning 18 and losing 19, with one game vacated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/notre-dame/|title=Notre Dame Fighting Irish Bowls|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com}}</ref> After an initial appearance in a postseason contest in the 1925 Rose Bowl, the Fighting Irish refused to participate in bowl games for more than four decades;<ref name=\"Time-Life, Inc\">{{cite journal|last1= Jenkins|first1= Dan|year= 1969|title= Knute Rockne Would Have Agreed, Ara|journal= Sports Illustrated|volume= 31|issue= 26|page= 26|publisher= Time-Life, Inc.|url= http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1083174/index.htm|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120326070443/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1083174/index.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date= March 26, 2012|accessdate= June 14, 2012|df= mdy-all}}</ref> writers like Dan Jenkins have speculated that Notre Dame might have gone to as many as twenty bowl games during the self-imposed forty-five-year hiatus.<ref name=\"Time-Life, Inc\"/> It has played in the [[BCS National Championship Game]] (1 loss), [[Rose Bowl Game|Rose Bowl]] (1 win), the [[Cotton Bowl Classic]] (5 wins, 2 losses), the [[Orange Bowl (game)|Orange Bowl]] (2 wins, 3 losses), the [[Sugar Bowl]] (2 wins, 2 losses), the [[Gator Bowl]] (1 win, 2 losses), the [[Liberty Bowl]] (1 win), the [[Aloha Bowl]] (1 loss), the [[Fiesta Bowl]] (1 win, 4 losses), the [[Independence Bowl]] (1 loss), the [[Buffalo Wild Wings Bowl|Insight Bowl]] (1 loss), [[Hawaii Bowl]] (1 win), the [[Sun Bowl]] (1 win), the [[Pinstripe Bowl]] (1 win) and the [[Citrus Bowl]] (1 win). From 1994 to the 2006 football seasons, Notre Dame lost 9 consecutive bowl games, tied with Northwestern University for the most in NCAA history. That streak ended with a 49\u201321 win over Hawaii in the 2008 Hawaii Bowl. In the process, Notre Dame scored its highest point total in post-season play. The record of 9 consecutive bowl losses was later tied by Northwestern in 2011, then that streak was snapped [[2013 Gator Bowl|a year later]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n{{CollegePrimaryHeader|team=Notre Dame Fighting Irish|Date|Bowl|Opponent|Result}}\n|-\n|January 1, 1925 || [[1925 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] || [[Stanford Cardinal football|Stanford]] || '''W''' 27\u201310\n|-\n|January 1, 1970 || [[1970 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] || #1 [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] || L 17\u201321\n|-\n|January 1, 1971 || [[1971 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] || #1 [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] || '''W''' 24\u201311\n|-\n|January 1, 1973 || [[1973 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] || #9 [[1972 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] || L 6\u201340\n|-\n|December 31, 1973 || [[1973 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] || #1 [[1973 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || '''W''' 24\u201323\n|-\n|January 1, 1975 || [[1975 Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl]] || #2 [[1974 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]] || '''W''' 13\u201311\n|-\n|December 27, 1976 || [[1976 Gator Bowl|Gator Bowl]] || #20 [[1976 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] || '''W''' 20\u20139\n|-\n|January 2, 1978 || [[1978 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] || #1 [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] || '''W''' 38\u201310\n|-\n|January 1, 1979 || [[1979 Cotton Bowl Classic|Cotton Bowl Classic]] || [[Houston Cougars football|Houston]] || '''W''' 35\u201334\n