{"title_page": "Undine (Columbia River sternwheeler)", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:Undine (sternwheeler) en route to Celilo Canal 1915.png|300px]]\n|Ship caption= ''Undine'' on [[Columbia River]] on way to opening of the [[Celilo Canal]], May 3, 1915.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name= ''Undine'' <small>(1887-1935)</small>; ''The Dalles'' <small>(1935-1940)</small>\n|Ship owner= [[Jacob Kamm|Vancouver Trans. Co.]] <small>(1888)</small>\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service= 1887\n|Ship out of service= 1940\n|Ship identification=  US #25266 <small>(1887-1921)</small>; #221499 <small>(1921-1935)</small>; #221499 <small>(1935-1940)</small>\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement= \n|Ship length= {{convert|150|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}<small>(1888-1917)</small>\n|Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}<small>(1888-1917)</small>\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth={{convert|6|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} depth of hold\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan= \n|Ship power =  twin steam engines, horizontally mounted: cylinder bore {{convert|16.25|in|cm|0|abbr=on}}; stroke {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion= stern-wheel\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship capacity= 450 passengers on excursions <small>(1890)</small>\n|Ship crew= \n|Ship notes= \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Undine''''' was a sternwheel-driven steamboat that operated from 1887 to 1935 on the [[Columbia River|Columbia]] and [[Willamette River|lower Willamette]] rivers.<ref name = Affleck27>{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter = Columbia River Waterways \u2014 List of Vessels\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = p.27\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  From 1935 to 1940 the same vessel was operated under the name ''The Dalles''.<ref name = Affleck26>{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter = Columbia River Waterways \u2014 List of Vessels\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = 26\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n''Undine'' was built at [[Portland, Oregon]] by shipbuilder J.H. Steffen for pioneer businessman [[Jacob Kamm]] and worked on the route along the [[Columbia River|lower Columbia river]] from Portland to [[Astoria, Oregon]].<ref name = Affleck27/>  ''Undine'' was rebuilt in 1917 for the [[Harkins Transportation Company]] and rebuilt again in 1921.<ref name = Affleck27/>  The Harkins line ran ''Undine'' until 1935 when it was sold and renamed '''''The Dalles'''''.<ref name = Affleck26/>  ''The Dalles'' was dismantled in 1940.<ref name = Affleck26/>\n\nThis vessel should not be confused with the Colorado River sternwheeler [[Undine (Colorado River sternwheeler)|''Undine'']].\n\n==Construction==\n''Undine'' was built by J.H. Steffen for [[Jacob Kamm]] and launched on January 3, 1888.<ref name = Wright354>{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = E.W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = Large Increase in British Columbia Inland and Ocean Steam Fleet\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA354#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]] \n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = 354\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' made its trial trip from [[Portland, Oregon]] to [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver, W.T.]] on Tuesday afternoon, March 20, 1888.<ref name = TrialTrip>{{Citation \n| title = The new steamer built by Jacob Kamm, the Undine, made her trial trip to Vancouver ...\n| url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn96061150/1888-03-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 30\n| issue  = 71\n| date = Mar 23, 1888\n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' made the 18 mile<ref name = NewSteamer>{{Citation \n| title = The Vancouver Transportation Company's new steamer Undine ...\n| type = source: Astoria Pioneer\n| url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022770/1888-05-11/ed-1/seq-2/\n| newspaper = Washington Standard\n| location = [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia, W.T.]]\n| volume = 28\n| issue  = 24\n| date = May 11, 1888\n| page  = 2, col.3\n| editor =\n| publisher = Johh Miller Murphy\n| nopp = yes}}</ref> return trip to Portland in one hour and twenty minutes.<ref name = TrialTrip/>  By May 1888, running for Kamm's Vancouver Transportation Company, Undine was able to cut the time from Vancouver to Portland down to 58 minutes running on 100 pounds of steam.<ref name = NewSteamer/>  Only two steamers had managed better time on this run, [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']] in 57 minutes, and [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|Telephone]], in 55 minutes.<ref name = NewSteamer/>\n\nAs built, ''Undine'' was {{convert|150|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} long, exclusive of the extension of the main deck over the stern, called the fantail, on which the stern-wheel was mounted.<ref name = Wright354/>  The beam was {{convert|27|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} (exclusive of [[guards (steamboat)|guards]] and the depth of hold was {{convert|6|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Wright354/>  The official merchant vessel registry number was 25266.<ref name = Affleck27/>\n\n''Undine'' was driven by a stern-wheel, which was turned by twin steam engines, horizontally mounted: cylinder bore {{convert|16.25|in|cm|abbr=on}}; stroke {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Wright354/>  The machinery was installed by C.W. Evans.<ref name = Wright354/>\n\n==Early career==\n''Undine'' was built for the route from Portland to [[Vancouver, Washington]].<ref name = Wright354/>  From 1888 to 1895 ''Undine'' ran primarily on this route, with occasional trips to [[Astoria, Oregon]] and excursion runs.<ref name = Wright354/>  ''Undine'' made its trial trip from Portland to Vancouver and return on Tuesday afternoon, March 20, 1888.<ref name = NewKammSteamer>{{Citation \n| title = The new steamer built by Jacob Kamm, the Undine, made her trial trip \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1888-03-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 30\n| issue  = 71\n| date = March 23, 1888 \n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The return trip to Portland took 120 minutes.<ref name = NewKammSteamer/>\n\nIn early May 1888, ''Undine'' made the 18 mile run from Vancouver to Portland in 58 minutes carrying 100 pounds of steam.<ref name = 58minutes>{{Citation \n| title = Territorial News \u2026 The Vancouver Transportation company's new steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022770/1888-05-11/ed-1/seq-2/\n| type = Source: Astoria Pioneer\n| newspaper = Washington Standard\n| location = Olympia, W.T.\n| volume = 28\n| issue  = 24\n| date = May 11, 1888\n| page  = 2, col.3\n| editor =\n| publisher = John Miller Murphy (1839-1916)\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' was then owned by the Vancouver Transportation Company.<ref name = 58minutes/>  This time had been beaten only twice before, once by [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']] in 57 minutes, and once by [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|''Telephone'']], in 55 minutes.<ref name = 58minutes/>\n\nOn August 24, 1890 it was reported that ''Undine'' had been sold and would be taken to [[Puget Sound]].<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Marine News and Notes\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1890-08-24/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = [[The Daily Astorian|Daily Morning Astorian]]\n| location = [[Astoria, Oregon|Astoria, OR]]\n| volume = 35\n| issue  = 54\n| date = August 24, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  This sale and transfer never occurred.\n\n===Excursion business===\n[[File:Undine ad 24 June 1898.jpg|thumb|Advertisement for excursion on Undine, placed June 24, 1898.]]\nIn May 1890, ''Undine'' could be chartered for $250 for an excursion from Portland to [[Oregon City, Oregon]].<ref name = PSday>{{Citation \n| title = Told by Correspondents \u2026 Public School Excursion \u2014 Four Hundred and Fifty Attend \u2014 A day of Pleasure \u2014 An Entire Success \u2014 Incidents of the Day\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/2011260136/1890-05-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = West Side\n| location = [[Independence, Oregon|Independence, OR]]\n| volume = 7\n| issue = 29\n| date = May 23, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.5\n| editor =\n| publisher = E.C. Pentland\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Other boats could be hired for much less.<ref name = PSday/>  An excursion ticket in May 1890 cost $1.00.<ref name = PSday/>  On a school excursion on the evening of Monday, May 19, 1890 from Portland to Oregon City, Undine carried 450 passengers, of which there were about 300 who paid fares.<ref name = PSday/>\n\nThere were professional organizers of steamboat excursions, one of whom in 1889 was J.J. Hauser.<ref name = Hauser>{{Citation \n| title = The steamer Undine came down on an excursion \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1889-07-28/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 24\n| date = July 28, 1889\n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Hauser\u2019s method was to book a band, charter a steamboat, and sell tickets, hopefully making a profit.<ref name = Hauser/>  Sometimes this worked for him, and he could make $200 on a single excursion, as he did on July 4, 1889, when he charted [[Multnomah (sternwheeler)|Multnomah]].<ref name = Hauser/>\n\nOther times, such as on Saturday, July 27, 1889, he lost money, about $150, when he charted ''Undine'' for a Portland-Astoria run, hired the band of the First Regiment, Oregon National Guard, but was not able to sell many tickets.<ref name = Hauser/>\n\nExcursion managers booked ''Undine'' for a trip from [[Newberg, Oregon]] up the Columbia river on Saturday, June 20, 1891.<ref name = 1891newberg>{{Citation \n| title = The excursion from Newberg that went up the Columbia on the steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn00063700/1891-06-26/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon City Enterprise\n| location = [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City, OR]]\n| volume = 25\n| issue  = 1\n| date = June 26, 1891\n| page  = 5, col.4\n| editor =\n| publisher = Chas. Meserve\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' carried 360 passengers on this excursion.<ref name = 1891newberg/>  The managers were said to have cleared $130.<ref name = 1891newberg/>\n\n===Towing work===\nSteamers like ''Undine'' were capable of being worked in multiple roles.  In addition to passenger and freight carriage, ''Undine'' was also used as a tow boat.  For example, on June 30, 1890, ''Undine'' towed a barge from [[Kalama, Washington]] laden with a steam locomotive and a passenger coach intended for the [[Ilwaco Railroad and Navigation Company]].<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Marine News and Notes \u2014 Interesting Items Regarding Vessels \u2026 The steamer Undine came down the river early this morning \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1890-06-30/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 34\n| issue  = 157\n| date = June 30, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.2\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n===Officers in the early years===\nCaptain Charles Tilton Kamm (1860-1906), son of [[Jacob Kamm]] (1823-1912), was master of ''Undine'' until 1892 when he was succeeded by Joseph H. Burgy (1851-1906), who commanded the boat at least through 1895.<ref name = Wright354/><ref>{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = Edgar W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = Organization of Pacific Coast S.S. Co., Fierce Competition on Ocean Routes\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = Portland, OR\n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = 260, n.25\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 97190356\n| name = Charles Tilton Kamm\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref name = GraveBurgy>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 56918241\n| name = Capt Joseph Herbert Burgy\n| accessdate = Jul 19, 2017\n }}</ref>  William S. Buchanan (1855-1912) also commanded ''Undine'' in August 1892.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = At Long Beach \u2026 Captain W.S. Buchanan \u2026\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12345DA148304870%25402412318-12316A95D185B3D8%25409-12D58541461AC268%2540At%252BSeaside%252BResorts%252BClatsopis%252BIs%252BThronged%252BWith%252BVisitors%252BThe%252BChatauqua%252BAssembly%252Bat%252BGearhart--Boating%252BParties&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 11\n| issue  = 28\n| date = August 7, 1892\n| page  = 10, col.4\n| editor = [[Harvey W. Scott|H.W. Scott]]\n| publisher = [[Henry Pittock|H.L.Pittock]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref name = Akin>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 138050984\n| name = Capt William Samuel \u201cBilly\u201d Buchanan\n| accessdate = April 14, 2020\n }}</ref>\n\nFor the most part of ''Undine''\u2019s early years, Fred S. Shepard (1844-1927) was the boat\u2019s chief engineer and Frank Malmquist (1861-1949) was its purser.<ref name = Wright354/><!-- Citation to Find a Grave used to establish family relationships, maiden names, and dates of birth and death only.--><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 65361992\n| name = Frederick S. Shepard\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 124683293\n| name = Frank Malmquist\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Men Roster Thins \u2014 Frank Malmquist\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12B57B3E76B4AA28%25402433276-12AEFF1843788912%254026-12B59F9563401410%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 58\n| issue  = 51\n| date = December 25, 1949\n| page  = Section Two, 5, col.8\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  W.S. Chapman was the steward of ''Undine'' in 1891.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Clackamas \u2026 W.S. Chapman, steward of the steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn00063700/1891-06-19/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon City Enterprise\n| location = Oregon City, OR\n| volume = 24\n| issue  = 52\n| date = June 19, 1891\n| page  = 1, col.6\n| editor =\n| publisher = Chas. Meserve\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  In October 1906, Capt Archibald L. \u201cScotty\u201d McNeill (1866-1935), pilot of [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']], took over command of ''Undine'' from Capt. Kane Olney.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Deck and Dock News\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042400/1906-10-03/ed-1/seq-8/\n| newspaper = Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 56\n| issue  = 263\n| date = October 3, 1906\n| page  = 8 col.2\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.S. Dellinger Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 127558841\n| name = Capt Archibald L McNeill\n| accessdate = July 23, 2017\n }}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nOn the night of September 3, 1891, near [[Vancouver, Washington]], crewmen on ''Undine'' found and recovered from the Columbia river the body of a Native American man whose hands had been tied by a chain wrapped around his body, and the chain secured to a heavy piece of railroad iron.<ref name = BodyFound>{{Citation \n| title = Sturgeon Jim Murdered \u2014 Found in the Columbia With His Hands Tied by a Chain\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045604/1891-09-05/ed-1/seq-2/\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., Sept. 4 (Special)\n| newspaper = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| volume = 20\n| issue  = 3\n| date = September 5, 1891\n| page  = 2, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = [[Leigh S. J. Hunt]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The body was later identified as that of one Sturgeon Jim, who resided near [[Washougal, Washington]], who had been missing for nine days since having a dispute with another man,<ref name = BodyFound/>  Murder charges were brought against the other man upon discovery of the body.<ref name = BodyFound/>\n\nOn March 24, 1898, a crew member on ''Undine'', S.H. Svensson, drowned at [[Rainier, Oregon]] while he and others were unloading a large cylinder from the steamer on to the dock.<ref name = Svensson>{{Citation \n| title = In the Several Courts \u2026 Against Vancouver Transportation\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238E00C38A488B8%25402414721-1231FCD210822A70%25407-12D540DA5619AF30%2540In%252BThe%252BSeveral%252BCourts%252BOpening%252BOf%252BThe%252BMarch%252BTerm%252BIn%252BThe%252BState%252BCircuit.%252BSuits%252BAgainst&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 39\n| issue  = 11,913\n| date = March 7, 1899\n| page  = 8, col.2\n| editor = [[Harvey W. Scott|H.W. Scott]]\n| publisher = [[Henry Pittock|H.L. Pittock]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref> Svensson\u2019s estate later filed a legal action against Vancouver Transportation Co.,seeking $5000 in damages and alleging that the company\u2019s negligence, specifically not securing the gangplank, insufficient lighting, and failure to properly tie up the steamer caused Svensson\u2019s death.<ref name = Svensson/>  Svensson left an aged father, a wife and four children as dependents.<ref name = Svensson/>\n\nOn April 17, 1906 Captain Burgy died in his cabin on board ''Undine''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Found Dead in His Cabin \u2014 Captain Joseph Burgy Expires from Heart Failure \u2014Pioneer River Captain Was Born on a Sailing Vessel on Gulf of Mexico\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-123ADE50C36C9258%25402417319-1231FC9427ADBAE8%254010-12D567758C057038%2540Found%252BDead%252BIn%252BHis%252BCabin%252BCaptain%252BJoseph%252BBurgy%252BExpires%252BFrom%252BHeart%252BFailure.%252BPioneer%252BRiver%252BCaptain&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 46\n| issue  = 14,152\n| date = April 18, 1906\n| page  = 11, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue of ''Telephone'' passengers==\nAt 3:00 a.m on January 5, 1891, after the elite sternwheeler [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|''Telephone'']], with William E. Larkins (1857-1908) in command, sank following a collision with the breakwater at the mouth of the [[Willamette River]], the eighty-five passengers of Telephone were taken off by [[Bonita (sternwheeler)|''Bonita'']], transferred to ''Undine'' and then carried into Portland.<ref name = TelephoneSunk>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Telephone Sunk \u2014 Lost in the Fog, She Runs Into the Willamette Breakwater\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045604/1892-01-06/ed-1/seq-3/\n| type = Dateline: Portland, Jan. 5 (Special)\n| newspaper = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| volume = 21\n| issue  = 52\n| date = January 6, 1891\n| page  = \n| editor =\n| publisher = [[Leigh S. J. Hunt]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 93265843\n| name = Capt William E Larkins\n| date = July 8, 2012\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref>  When ''Telephone'' did not arrive on time in Portland, there were concerns that the boat had been sunk, perhaps in the middle of the river by colliding with one of the many large snags or saw logs that were common at that time.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>\n\nWhen ''Undine'' came into the dock at Portland at 10:15&nbsp;a.m., there were many shouted inquiries from the people gathered ashore about the ''Telephone''.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>  The reply from ''Undine'', \u201cPassengers all safe and aboard this boat\u201d was received gladly by the crowd.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>\n\n==Troop transport==\nOn May 12, 1894 regular U.S. army troops, 225 in number, from the [[Vancouver Army Barracks]] were ordered to proceed to [[Seattle, Washington]] to address the civil disturbances that had arisen in connection with [[Coxey\u2019s Army]].<ref name = Coxey1>{{Citation \n| title = Regulars Ordered to Seattle\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1894-05-13/ed-1/seq-1/\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash, May 12.\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 42\n| issue  = 3\n| date = May 13, 1894\n| page  = 1, cols.3\u20134\n| editor =\n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' transported the troops from Vancouver to [[Kalama, Washington]] where they disembarked to proceed to Seattle by train.<ref name = Coxey1/>  On May 30, 1894, the four companies of troops returned to the Vancouver Barracks from Seattle, being carried from Kalama to Vancouver on ''Undine''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Other Northwest News \u2014 The Troops Have Returned\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12369B3E27968198%25402412980-12316AEA8C375990%25401-12D510D629ACABB0%2540Northwest%252BNews%252BA%252B%25255BIllegible%25255D%252BOf%252BBeautiful%252BFlowers%252BNotwithstanding%252Bthe%252BInclement%252BWeather%25252C%252BTribute%252Bto%252Bthe%252BHonored&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., May 30.\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 10,894\n| date = May 31, 1894\n| page  = 2, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n== Portland-Vancouver route 1895 ==\n[[File:Undine (sternwheeler) June 1894, Clark County, Washington.png|thumb|Undine at [[Clark County, Washington|Clark County, WA]], June 1894.]]\nAs of 1895 ''Undine'' was making two round trips a day, Sundays excepted, on the Portland-Vancouver route.<ref name = Wright354/>  In January 1896 ''Undine'', under Captain Charles T. Kamm, departed from Vancouver twice a day at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. and 1:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name = 1896jan24>{{Citation \n| title = Vancouver Transportation Co.\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238EA3FA129F5B0%25402413583-12384C4A5A1C9DB8%25409-12D556626DF39490%2540No%252BHeadline&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = advertisement\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 11,329\n| date = January 24, 1896\n| page  = 10, col.7\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' left Portland from the Taylor Street dock at 10:30&nbsp;a.m. and 4:30&nbsp;p.m. for Vancouver.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  For freight or passage, application was made on board.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  Round trip fare was 25 cents.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  ''Undine'' continued on this schedule until at least April 28, 1900.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Vancouver Transportation Co.\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238E1DB6D29A158%25402415138-1231FCB5B1F108C0%254010-12D544BFA07130E8%2540No%252BHeadline&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = advertisement\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 40\n| issue  = 12,285\n| date = April 28, 1900\n| page  = 11, col.5\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 1896, ''Undine'' broke a stern-wheel shaft near the mouth of the [[Willamette River]].<ref name = Shaft1896>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Undine Broke Her Shaft\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12388FC2D5328B50%25402413766-1231FC2D1B831B28%25405-12D53960005CAE90%2540Afloat%252BAnd%252BAshore%252BThe%252BFulwood%252BCame%252BAround%252BThe%252BHorn%252BSafely.%252BSnake%252BRiver%252BBusiness--Oriental%252BFlour&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., July 24.\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 36\n| issue  = 11,486\n| date = July 25, 1896\n| page  = 6, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott]\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The initial plan was to have ''Undine'' taken out of service for about 10 days, during which it would replaced on its route by [[Mascot (sternwheeler)|''Mascot'']].<ref name = Shaft1896/>  This changed to keeping it in service with only one engine operating.<ref name = MNjuly28>{{Citation \n| title = Marine Notes\n| url = \n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = \n| issue  = \n| date = July 28, 1896\n| page  = 3, col\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  On July 27, 1896 ''Undine'' made the run from Vancouver to Portland with one engine in one hour and 28 minutes.<ref name = MNjuly28/>\n\n==Columbia Gorge route==\nIn March 1905 ''Undine'' was hauled out, for the first time in twelve years, at the Portland Shipbuilding Company\u2019s yard.<ref name = 1905haulout>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Hauled Out \u2014 Hull Is in Almost Perfect Condition After Twelve Years Service\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1235F26E2E8F0D58%25402416924-1231FDA68B7E5648%254013-125BDDC5FADB3CCB%2540Buford%252BDue%252BToday%252BTransport%252BBringing%252BTwo%252BBatteries%252Bof%252BArtillery.%252BTakes%252BOut%252BThe%252BNineteenth%252BWill%252BSall&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 24\n| issue  = 12\n| date = March 19, 1905\n| page  = 14, col.3\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The hull was found to be in remarkably good condition, requiring replacement of only a few planks at the bow and the stern.<ref name = 1905haulout/>  ''Undine'' was scheduled for a thorough overall of its machinery and structure, which was expected to take about two months.<ref name = 1905haulout/>\n\nIn August 1905 ''Undine'' was employed on sightseeing trips up the Columbia River to [[Cascade Locks and Canal]].<ref name = 1905excursions>{{Citation \n| title = Scenery of Columbia \u2014 Great Up-River Trip Is Best Made on the Undine\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12383B17776F77A0%25402417062-1231FD772A62E038%254015-125D38AA01FCEE3E%2540Scenery%252BOf%252BColumbia.%252BGreat%252BUp-River%252BTrip%252BIs%252BBest%252BMade%252Bon%252Bthe%252BUndine&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 45\n| issue  = 13,933\n| date = August 4, 1905\n| page  = 16, col.1\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' departed from the Taylor Street dock at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. and returned at 6:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name = 1905excursions/>  Round trip fare was $1.50.<ref name = 1905excursions/>\n\nOn February 11, 1906, ''Undine'' was secured by The Dalles, Portland & Astoria Navigation Company, also known as the Regulator Line, to connect with the sternwheeler [[Bailey Gatzert (sternwheeler)|''Bailey Gatzert'']] at the [[Cascades of the Columbia|Cascades]] on the route up the Columbia river to [[The Dalles, Oregon]].<ref name = ToUpperRiver>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Goes on Upper River\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-123ADDAF8CD5B888%25402417255-1231FC890E8E6508%254011-12D599A561C6F518%2540Fireboat%252BIs%252BLeaking%252BGovernment%252BInspectors%252BRecommend%252BImmediate%252BRepairs.%252BCity%252BOfficials%252BNotified%252BHall%252BNeeds%252BRecaulking%252Band&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 46\n| issue  = 14,098\n| date = February 12, 1906\n| page  = 12, col.5\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The change was made necessary by need to find a replacement for the sternwheeler [[Dalles City (sternwheeler)|''Dalles City'']], which had sunk at Curtis Landing a few days before.<ref name = ToUpperRiver/>\n\n''Dalles City'' was returned to service on March 16, 1906, after which ''Undine'' was hauled out at Portland Shipbuilding for a hull inspection.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Along the Waterfront\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-03-17/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = [[The Oregon Journal|Oregon Daily Journal]]\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 10\n| date = March 17, 1906\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor = [[Sam Jackson (publisher)|C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson]]\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' was back in service a few days later, on the Vancouver route.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Along the Waterfront\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-03-20/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Oregon Daily Journal\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 12\n| date = March 20, 1906\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor = C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Funeral of Sheriff John R. Shaver==\nOn May 2, 1906, a funeral was held at the Oregon City courthouse for John R. Shaver, sheriff of [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas County]], who had been shot a few days earlier by desperado Frank Smith near [[Woodburn, Oregon]].<ref name = LastTribute>{{Citation \n| title = Hundreds Pay Last Tribute To Victim of Outlaw Smith \u2014 Business Suspended in Oregon City Out of Respect to Late Sheriff Shaver \u2014 Morbidly Curious View Body of Dead Outlaw \u2014 Jury Returns Verdict That Officer Shot Him in Performance of Duty and That Bandit Was Murderer of Three Men\n| type = Dateline: Oregon City, Or. May 2 (Special Dispatch to The Journal).\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-05-02/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon Daily Journal\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 49\n| date = May 2, 1906\n| page  = 1, col.4\n| editor = C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Although he had chosen a career in law enforcement, Shaver was a member of a [[Shaver Transportation Company|prominent steamboating family]].  At the conclusion of the funeral, ''Undine'' carried the remains to [[River View Cemetery (Portland, Oregon)|River View Cemetery]] to be interred in the Shaver family plot.<ref name = LastTribute/>\n\n==Opening of Celilo Canal==\n[[File:Undine Reynolds cartoon 1915.jpg|thumb|Cartoon published in the ''Morning Oregonian'', marking the transit of ''Undine'' from Portland to [[Lewiston, Idaho]] through the newly completed [[Celilo Canal]], May 1915]]\nWhen the [[Celilo Canal]] was opened in 1915, ''Undine'', carrying a number of dignitaries, became the first steamboat to transit the canal downstream from [[Celilo, Oregon|Celilo]] to [[Astoria, Oregon]].<ref>{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = Seattle, WA\n| chapter = Maritime Events of 1915\n| pages = 253\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}</ref>\n\nIn late April 1932, ''Undine'' was operated by the Mid-Columbia Navigation Company, which announced plans for ''Undine'' to make its first run on a route from Portland to [[The Dalles, Oregon]], arriving on at The Dalles on the night of April 26, 1932 with a cargo from Portland of sugar.<ref name = OnSchedule>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Runs on Schedule\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A00E90172CF279%25402426825-1299CDA5AC753A3A%254016-1299CDA5AC753A3A%2540%2Fhlterms%3A%2522steamer%2520Undine%2522&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: [[The Dalles, Oregon|The Dalles, Or.]], April 26 (Special).\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,299\n| date = April 27, 1932\n| page  = 17, col.8\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' would return to Portland with a new crop of wool brought in by trucks from [[Yakima, Washington]].<ref name = OnSchedule/>\n\nThe Mid-Columbia Navigation Company was organized by Thomas Larkin, president and general manager, L.N. Chambreau, traffic representative, Edward Spockerman, general manager, Robert Irish, purchasing manager, Frank Raicy, vice-president and assistant manager, C.C. Thompson, secretary and treasurer, and Harold Johnston, counsel.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Portland-The Dalles Steamer Service Inaugurated\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A009894287EEF3%25402426822-1299D022F7A96B0D%254016-12A013494B38ED8D%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Photograph and caption\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 51\n| issue  = 17\n| date = April 24, 1932\n| page  = 17, cols.2\u20133\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Forced sale==\nOn July 11, 1932, crewmen who were employed on ''Undine'' during March and April of that year brought suit in the United States District Court to force the sale of the steamer and \u201cher engines, tackle, apparatus and furniture\u201d to satisfy their claims for wages.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Sale of Steamer Sought\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A0BB0E1513F476%25402426901-1299CE19CBEFF5F4%254014-12A12571350295A8%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,364\n| date = July 12, 1932\n| page  = 15, col.4\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The case name was ''Samuel H. Shaver et al. vs. Steamer Undine''.<ref name = Motion2Sell>{{Citation \n| title = Motion Calendar Up \u2014 Federal Judge McNary to Hear Cases in Law Today\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A0C36A7B784036%25402426921-1299D2C7173121D4%25406-12A19B226CCFB42F%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,381\n| date = August 1, 1932\n| page  = 7, cols.3\u20134\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  On August 1, 1932 a motion for an order to the U.S. marshal to sell the boat was presented for hearing before U.S. district court judge [[John Hugh McNary|John H. McNary]] (1867-1936).<ref name = Motion2Sell/>  In November 1932, by order of the court, the U.S. Marshal service sold ''Undine'' to William Greenberg.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = River Vessel Bought\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A269996D6B96EA%25402427116-1299E09666B83E0C%254011-12A2B2C732BE99CB%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 52\n| issue  = 7\n| date = February 12, 1933\n| page  = 12, cols.2\u20133\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Change of name to ''The Dalles''==\nOn October 31, 1935, the Bureau of Navigation and Steamboat Inspection, Milton A. Miller (1861-1938), Collector of Customs, announced that it had granted permission to ''Undine'', official number 221499, to change its name to ''The Dalles''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Miscellaneous \u2026 The Bureau of Navigation and Steamboat Inspection \u2026\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A507BEB6E513F1%25402428107-12A072ADF40BD345%254010-12A5D1276D3B8338%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 74\n| issue  = 23,398\n| date = October 31, 1935\n| page  = 11, col.11\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 29385157\n| name = Milton Armington Miller\n| accessdate = July 23, 2017\n }}</ref>\n\n==Disposition==\n''The Dalles'' (ex ''Undine'') was scrapped in 1940.<ref>{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| chapter = \n| pages = 484\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Undine (sternwheeler)}}\n\n=== Printed sources===\n* <!-- AFFLECK, CENTURY OF PADDLEWHEELERS -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter =\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- MILLS, STERNWHEELERS UP COLUMBIA -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Mills \n| author1-first = Randall V. \n| author-link1 = Randall V. Mills \n| title = Sternwheelers up Columbia -- A Century of Steamboating in the Oregon Country | isbn = 0-8032-5874-7 \n| chapter =\n| lccn = 77007161 \n| location =  Lincoln NE \n| publisher = University of Nebraska \n| date = 1947 \n| pages = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- NEWELL, ed. H.W. McCURDY MARINE HISTORY -->{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| chapter = \n| pages = 253, 308, 324, 484, 567\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}\n* <!-- TIMMEN, BLOW FOR THE LANDING -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Timmen \n| author1-first = Fritz\n| title = Blow for the Landing -- A Hundred Years of Steam Navigation on the Waters of the West \n| isbn = 0-87004-221-1 \n| lccn = 73150815 \n| location =  Caldwell, ID \n| publisher =  [[Caxton Press (United States)|Caxton Printers]] \n| date = 1973 \n| pages = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- WRIGHT, ed. LEWIS AND DRYDEN MARINE HISTORY -->{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = E.W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = \n| chapter-url = \n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]] \n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = \n| nopp = yes}}\n\n=== On-line newspapers and journals ===\n* <!-- HISTORIC OREGON NEWSPAPERS-->{{cite web\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu\n| title = Historic Oregon Newspapers\n| publisher = [[University of Oregon]]\n| accessdate = \n}}\n* <!-- CHRONICLING AMERICA (LoC)-->{{cite web\n| url  = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov\n| title = Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers\n| publisher = [[Library of Congress]]\n| accessdate = \n}}\n\n{{Steamboats Pacific Northwest}}\n\n[[Category:Paddle steamers]]\n[[Category:Steamboats of the Columbia River]]\n[[Category:1867 ships]]\n[[Category:Steamboats of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin|display title=ital}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=[[File:Undine (sternwheeler) en route to Celilo Canal 1915.png|300px]]\n|Ship caption= ''Undine'' on [[Columbia River]] on way to opening of the [[Celilo Canal]], May 3, 1915.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship name= ''Undine'' <small>(1887-1935)</small>; ''The Dalles'' <small>(1935-1940)</small>\n|Ship owner= [[Jacob Kamm|Vancouver Trans. Co.]] <small>(1888)</small>\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service= 1887\n|Ship out of service= 1940\n|Ship identification=  US #25266 <small>(1887-1921)</small>; #221499 <small>(1921-1935)</small>; #221499 <small>(1935-1940)</small>\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement= \n|Ship length= {{convert|150|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}<small>(1888-1917)</small>\n|Ship beam={{convert|27|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}<small>(1888-1917)</small>\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth={{convert|6|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} depth of hold\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship sail plan= \n|Ship power =  twin steam engines, horizontally mounted: cylinder bore {{convert|16.25|in|cm|0|abbr=on}}; stroke {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|1|abbr=on}}\n|Ship propulsion= stern-wheel\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship capacity= 450 passengers on excursions <small>(1890)</small>\n|Ship crew= \n|Ship notes= \n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Undine''''' was a sternwheel-driven steamboat that operated from 1887 to 1935 on the [[Columbia River|Columbia]] and [[Willamette River|lower Willamette]] rivers.<ref name = Affleck27>{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter = Columbia River Waterways \u2014 List of Vessels\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = p.27\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  From 1935 to 1940 the same vessel was operated under the name ''The Dalles''.<ref name = Affleck26>{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter = Columbia River Waterways \u2014 List of Vessels\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = 26\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n''Undine'' was built at [[Portland, Oregon]] by shipbuilder J.H. Steffen for pioneer businessman [[Jacob Kamm]] and worked on the route along the [[Columbia River|lower Columbia river]] from Portland to [[Astoria, Oregon]].<ref name = Affleck27/>  ''Undine'' was rebuilt in 1917 for the [[Harkins Transportation Company]] and rebuilt again in 1921.<ref name = Affleck27/>  The Harkins line ran ''Undine'' until 1935 when it was sold and renamed '''''The Dalles'''''.<ref name = Affleck26/>  ''The Dalles'' was dismantled in 1940.<ref name = Affleck26/>\n\nThis vessel should not be confused with the Colorado River sternwheeler [[Undine (Colorado River sternwheeler|''Undine'']].\n\n==Construction==\n''Undine'' was built by J.H. Steffen for [[Jacob Kamm]] and launched on January 3, 1888.<ref name = Wright354>{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = E.W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = Large Increase in British Columbia Inland and Ocean Steam Fleet\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA354#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]] \n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = 354\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' made its trial trip from [[Portland, Oregon]] to [[Vancouver, Washington|Vancouver, W.T.]] on Tuesday afternoon, March 20, 1888.<ref name = TrialTrip>{{Citation \n| title = The new steamer built by Jacob Kamm, the Undine, made her trial trip to Vancouver ...\n| url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn96061150/1888-03-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 30\n| issue  = 71\n| date = Mar 23, 1888\n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' made the 18 mile<ref name = NewSteamer>{{Citation \n| title = The Vancouver Transportation Company's new steamer Undine ...\n| type = source: Astoria Pioneer\n| url = https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022770/1888-05-11/ed-1/seq-2/\n| newspaper = Washington Standard\n| location = [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia, W.T.]]\n| volume = 28\n| issue  = 24\n| date = May 11, 1888\n| page  = 2, col.3\n| editor =\n| publisher = Johh Miller Murphy\n| nopp = yes}}</ref> return trip to Portland in one hour and twenty minutes.<ref name = TrialTrip/>  By May 1888, running for Kamm's Vancouver Transportation Company, Undine was able to cut the time from Vancouver to Portland down to 58 minutes running on 100 pounds of steam.<ref name = NewSteamer/>  Only two steamers had managed better time on this run, [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']] in 57 minutes, and [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|Telephone]], in 55 minutes.<ref name = NewSteamer/>\n\nAs built, ''Undine'' was {{convert|150|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} long, exclusive of the extension of the main deck over the stern, called the fantail, on which the stern-wheel was mounted.<ref name = Wright354/>  The beam was {{convert|27|ft|m|2|abbr=on}} (exclusive of [[guards (steamboat)|guards]] and the depth of hold was {{convert|6|ft|m|2|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Wright354/>  The official merchant vessel registry number was 25266.<ref name = Affleck27/>\n\n''Undine'' was driven by a stern-wheel, which was turned by twin steam engines, horizontally mounted: cylinder bore {{convert|16.25|in|cm|abbr=on}}; stroke {{convert|6|ft|0|in|cm|abbr=on}}.<ref name = Wright354/>  The machinery was installed by C.W. Evans.<ref name = Wright354/>\n\n==Early career==\n''Undine'' was built for the route from Portland to [[Vancouver, Washington]].<ref name = Wright354/>  From 1888 to 1895 ''Undine'' ran primarily on this route, with occasional trips to [[Astoria, Oregon]] and excursion runs.<ref name = Wright354/>  ''Undine'' made its trial trip from Portland to Vancouver and return on Tuesday afternoon, March 20, 1888.<ref name = NewKammSteamer>{{Citation \n| title = The new steamer built by Jacob Kamm, the Undine, made her trial trip \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1888-03-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 30\n| issue  = 71\n| date = March 23, 1888 \n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The return trip to Portland took 120 minutes.<ref name = NewKammSteamer/>\n\nIn early May 1888, ''Undine'' made the 18 mile run from Vancouver to Portland in 58 minutes carrying 100 pounds of steam.<ref name = 58minutes>{{Citation \n| title = Territorial News \u2026 The Vancouver Transportation company's new steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84022770/1888-05-11/ed-1/seq-2/\n| type = Source: Astoria Pioneer\n| newspaper = Washington Standard\n| location = Olympia, W.T.\n| volume = 28\n| issue  = 24\n| date = May 11, 1888\n| page  = 2, col.3\n| editor =\n| publisher = John Miller Murphy (1839-1916)\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' was then owned by the Vancouver Transportation Company.<ref name = 58minutes/>  This time had been beaten only twice before, once by [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']] in 57 minutes, and once by [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|''Telephone'']], in 55 minutes.<ref name = 58minutes/>\n\nOn August 24, 1890 it was reported that ''Undine'' had been sold and would be taken to [[Puget Sound]].<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Marine News and Notes\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1890-08-24/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = [[The Daily Astorian|Daily Morning Astorian]]\n| location = [[Astoria, Oregon|Astoria, OR]]\n| volume = 35\n| issue  = 54\n| date = August 24, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  This sale and transfer never occurred.\n\n===Excursion business===\n[[File:Undine ad 24 June 1898.jpg|thumb|Advertisement for excursion on Undine, placed June 24, 1898.]]\nIn May 1890, ''Undine'' could be chartered for $250 for an excursion from Portland to [[Oregon City, Oregon]].<ref name = PSday>{{Citation \n| title = Told by Correspondents \u2026 Public School Excursion \u2014 Four Hundred and Fifty Attend \u2014 A day of Pleasure \u2014 An Entire Success \u2014 Incidents of the Day\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/2011260136/1890-05-23/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = West Side\n| location = [[Independence, Oregon|Independence, OR]]\n| volume = 7\n| issue = 29\n| date = May 23, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.5\n| editor =\n| publisher = E.C. Pentland\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Other boats could be hired for much less.<ref name = PSday/>  An excursion ticket in May 1890 cost $1.00.<ref name = PSday/>  On a school excursion on the evening of Monday, May 19, 1890 from Portland to Oregon City, Undine carried 450 passengers, of which there were about 300 who paid fares.<ref name = PSday/>\n\nThere were professional organizers of steamboat excursions, one of whom in 1889 was J.J. Hauser.<ref name = Hauser>{{Citation \n| title = The steamer Undine came down on an excursion \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1889-07-28/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 24\n| date = July 28, 1889\n| page  = 3, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Hauser\u2019s method was to book a band, charter a steamboat, and sell tickets, hopefully making a profit.<ref name = Hauser/>  Sometimes this worked for him, and he could make $200 on a single excursion, as he did on July 4, 1889, when he charted [[Multnomah (sternwheeler)|Multnomah]].<ref name = Hauser/>\n\nOther times, such as on Saturday, July 27, 1889, he lost money, about $150, when he charted ''Undine'' for a Portland-Astoria run, hired the band of the First Regiment, Oregon National Guard, but was not able to sell many tickets.<ref name = Hauser/>\n\nExcursion managers booked ''Undine'' for a trip from [[Newberg, Oregon]] up the Columbia river on Saturday, June 20, 1891.<ref name = 1891newberg>{{Citation \n| title = The excursion from Newberg that went up the Columbia on the steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn00063700/1891-06-26/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon City Enterprise\n| location = [[Oregon City, Oregon|Oregon City, OR]]\n| volume = 25\n| issue  = 1\n| date = June 26, 1891\n| page  = 5, col.4\n| editor =\n| publisher = Chas. Meserve\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' carried 360 passengers on this excursion.<ref name = 1891newberg/>  The managers were said to have cleared $130.<ref name = 1891newberg/>\n\n===Towing work===\nSteamers like ''Undine'' were capable of being worked in multiple roles.  In addition to passenger and freight carriage, ''Undine'' was also used as a tow boat.  For example, on June 30, 1890, ''Undine'' towed a barge from [[Kalama, Washington]] laden with a steam locomotive and a passenger coach intended for the [[Ilwaco Railroad and Navigation Company]].<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Marine News and Notes \u2014 Interesting Items Regarding Vessels \u2026 The steamer Undine came down the river early this morning \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1890-06-30/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 34\n| issue  = 157\n| date = June 30, 1890\n| page  = 3, col.2\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.F. Halloran & Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n===Officers in the early years===\nCaptain Charles Tilton Kamm (1860-1906), son of [[Jacob Kamm]] (1823-1912), was master of ''Undine'' until 1892 when he was succeeded by Joseph H. Burgy (1851-1906), who commanded the boat at least through 1895.<ref name = Wright354/><ref>{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = Edgar W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = Organization of Pacific Coast S.S. Co., Fierce Competition on Ocean Routes\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = Portland, OR\n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = 260, n.25\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 97190356\n| name = Charles Tilton Kamm\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref name = GraveBurgy>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 56918241\n| name = Capt Joseph Herbert Burgy\n| accessdate = Jul 19, 2017\n }}</ref>  William S. Buchanan (1855-1912) also commanded ''Undine'' in August 1892.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = At Long Beach \u2026 Captain W.S. Buchanan \u2026\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12345DA148304870%25402412318-12316A95D185B3D8%25409-12D58541461AC268%2540At%252BSeaside%252BResorts%252BClatsopis%252BIs%252BThronged%252BWith%252BVisitors%252BThe%252BChatauqua%252BAssembly%252Bat%252BGearhart--Boating%252BParties&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 11\n| issue  = 28\n| date = August 7, 1892\n| page  = 10, col.4\n| editor = [[Harvey W. Scott|H.W. Scott]]\n| publisher = [[Henry Pittock|H.L.Pittock]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref name = Akin>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 138050984\n| name = Capt William Samuel \u201cBilly\u201d Buchanan\n| accessdate = April 14, 2020\n }}</ref>\n\nFor the most part of ''Undine''\u2019s early years, Fred S. Shepard (1844-1927) was the boat\u2019s chief engineer and Frank Malmquist (1861-1949) was its purser.<ref name = Wright354/><!-- Citation to Find a Grave used to establish family relationships, maiden names, and dates of birth and death only.--><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 65361992\n| name = Frederick S. Shepard\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 124683293\n| name = Frank Malmquist\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref><ref>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Men Roster Thins \u2014 Frank Malmquist\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12B57B3E76B4AA28%25402433276-12AEFF1843788912%254026-12B59F9563401410%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 58\n| issue  = 51\n| date = December 25, 1949\n| page  = Section Two, 5, col.8\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  W.S. Chapman was the steward of ''Undine'' in 1891.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Clackamas \u2026 W.S. Chapman, steward of the steamer Undine \u2026\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn00063700/1891-06-19/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon City Enterprise\n| location = Oregon City, OR\n| volume = 24\n| issue  = 52\n| date = June 19, 1891\n| page  = 1, col.6\n| editor =\n| publisher = Chas. Meserve\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  In October 1906, Capt Archibald L. \u201cScotty\u201d McNeill (1866-1935), pilot of [[Lurline (sternwheeler 1878)|''Lurline'']], took over command of ''Undine'' from Capt. Kane Olney.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Deck and Dock News\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042400/1906-10-03/ed-1/seq-8/\n| newspaper = Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 56\n| issue  = 263\n| date = October 3, 1906\n| page  = 8 col.2\n| editor =\n| publisher = J.S. Dellinger Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 127558841\n| name = Capt Archibald L McNeill\n| accessdate = July 23, 2017\n }}</ref>\n\n==Casualties==\nOn the night of September 3, 1891, near [[Vancouver, Washington]], crewmen on ''Undine'' found and recovered from the Columbia river the body of a Native American man whose hands had been tied by a chain wrapped around his body, and the chain secured to a heavy piece of railroad iron.<ref name = BodyFound>{{Citation \n| title = Sturgeon Jim Murdered \u2014 Found in the Columbia With His Hands Tied by a Chain\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045604/1891-09-05/ed-1/seq-2/\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., Sept. 4 (Special)\n| newspaper = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| volume = 20\n| issue  = 3\n| date = September 5, 1891\n| page  = 2, col.1\n| editor =\n| publisher = [[Leigh S. J. Hunt]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The body was later identified as that of one Sturgeon Jim, who resided near [[Washougal, Washington]], who had been missing for nine days since having a dispute with another man,<ref name = BodyFound/>  Murder charges were brought against the other man upon discovery of the body.<ref name = BodyFound/>\n\nOn March 24, 1898, a crew member on ''Undine'', S.H. Svensson, drowned at [[Rainier, Oregon]] while he and others were unloading a large cylinder from the steamer on to the dock.<ref name = Svensson>{{Citation \n| title = In the Several Courts \u2026 Against Vancouver Transportation\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238E00C38A488B8%25402414721-1231FCD210822A70%25407-12D540DA5619AF30%2540In%252BThe%252BSeveral%252BCourts%252BOpening%252BOf%252BThe%252BMarch%252BTerm%252BIn%252BThe%252BState%252BCircuit.%252BSuits%252BAgainst&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 39\n| issue  = 11,913\n| date = March 7, 1899\n| page  = 8, col.2\n| editor = [[Harvey W. Scott|H.W. Scott]]\n| publisher = [[Henry Pittock|H.L. Pittock]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref> Svensson\u2019s estate later filed a legal action against Vancouver Transportation Co.,seeking $5000 in damages and alleging that the company\u2019s negligence, specifically not securing the gangplank, insufficient lighting, and failure to properly tie up the steamer caused Svensson\u2019s death.<ref name = Svensson/>  Svensson left an aged father, a wife and four children as dependents.<ref name = Svensson/>\n\nOn April 17, 1906 Captain Burgy died in his cabin on board ''Undine''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Found Dead in His Cabin \u2014 Captain Joseph Burgy Expires from Heart Failure \u2014Pioneer River Captain Was Born on a Sailing Vessel on Gulf of Mexico\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-123ADE50C36C9258%25402417319-1231FC9427ADBAE8%254010-12D567758C057038%2540Found%252BDead%252BIn%252BHis%252BCabin%252BCaptain%252BJoseph%252BBurgy%252BExpires%252BFrom%252BHeart%252BFailure.%252BPioneer%252BRiver%252BCaptain&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 46\n| issue  = 14,152\n| date = April 18, 1906\n| page  = 11, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Rescue of ''Telephone'' passengers==\nAt 3:00 a.m on January 5, 1891, after the elite sternwheeler [[Telephone (sternwheeler)|''Telephone'']], with William E. Larkins (1857-1908) in command, sank following a collision with the breakwater at the mouth of the [[Willamette River]], the eighty-five passengers of Telephone were taken off by [[Bonita (sternwheeler)|''Bonita'']], transferred to ''Undine'' and then carried into Portland.<ref name = TelephoneSunk>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Telephone Sunk \u2014 Lost in the Fog, She Runs Into the Willamette Breakwater\n| url = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045604/1892-01-06/ed-1/seq-3/\n| type = Dateline: Portland, Jan. 5 (Special)\n| newspaper = [[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]]\n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| volume = 21\n| issue  = 52\n| date = January 6, 1891\n| page  = \n| editor =\n| publisher = [[Leigh S. J. Hunt]]\n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 93265843\n| name = Capt William E Larkins\n| date = July 8, 2012\n| accessdate = July 19, 2017\n }}</ref>  When ''Telephone'' did not arrive on time in Portland, there were concerns that the boat had been sunk, perhaps in the middle of the river by colliding with one of the many large snags or saw logs that were common at that time.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>\n\nWhen ''Undine'' came into the dock at Portland at 10:15&nbsp;a.m., there were many shouted inquiries from the people gathered ashore about the ''Telephone''.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>  The reply from ''Undine'', \u201cPassengers all safe and aboard this boat\u201d was received gladly by the crowd.<ref name = TelephoneSunk/>\n\n==Troop transport==\nOn May 12, 1894 regular U.S. army troops, 225 in number, from the [[Vancouver Army Barracks]] were ordered to proceed to [[Seattle, Washington]] to address the civil disturbances that had arisen in connection with [[Coxey\u2019s Army]].<ref name = Coxey1>{{Citation \n| title = Regulars Ordered to Seattle\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn96061150/1894-05-13/ed-1/seq-1/\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash, May 12.\n| newspaper = Daily Morning Astorian\n| location = Astoria, OR\n| volume = 42\n| issue  = 3\n| date = May 13, 1894\n| page  = 1, cols.3\u20134\n| editor =\n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' transported the troops from Vancouver to [[Kalama, Washington]] where they disembarked to proceed to Seattle by train.<ref name = Coxey1/>  On May 30, 1894, the four companies of troops returned to the Vancouver Barracks from Seattle, being carried from Kalama to Vancouver on ''Undine''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Other Northwest News \u2014 The Troops Have Returned\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12369B3E27968198%25402412980-12316AEA8C375990%25401-12D510D629ACABB0%2540Northwest%252BNews%252BA%252B%25255BIllegible%25255D%252BOf%252BBeautiful%252BFlowers%252BNotwithstanding%252Bthe%252BInclement%252BWeather%25252C%252BTribute%252Bto%252Bthe%252BHonored&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., May 30.\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 10,894\n| date = May 31, 1894\n| page  = 2, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n== Portland-Vancouver route 1895 ==\n[[File:Undine (sternwheeler) June 1894, Clark County, Washington.png|thumb|Undine at [[Clark County, Washington|Clark County, WA]], June 1894.]]\nAs of 1895 ''Undine'' was making two round trips a day, Sundays excepted, on the Portland-Vancouver route.<ref name = Wright354/>  In January 1896 ''Undine'', under Captain Charles T. Kamm, departed from Vancouver twice a day at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. and 1:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name = 1896jan24>{{Citation \n| title = Vancouver Transportation Co.\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238EA3FA129F5B0%25402413583-12384C4A5A1C9DB8%25409-12D556626DF39490%2540No%252BHeadline&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = advertisement\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 33\n| issue  = 11,329\n| date = January 24, 1896\n| page  = 10, col.7\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' left Portland from the Taylor Street dock at 10:30&nbsp;a.m. and 4:30&nbsp;p.m. for Vancouver.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  For freight or passage, application was made on board.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  Round trip fare was 25 cents.<ref name = 1896jan24/>  ''Undine'' continued on this schedule until at least April 28, 1900.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Vancouver Transportation Co.\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1238E1DB6D29A158%25402415138-1231FCB5B1F108C0%254010-12D544BFA07130E8%2540No%252BHeadline&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = advertisement\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 40\n| issue  = 12,285\n| date = April 28, 1900\n| page  = 11, col.5\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\nOn July 24, 1896, ''Undine'' broke a stern-wheel shaft near the mouth of the [[Willamette River]].<ref name = Shaft1896>{{Citation \n| title = Steamer Undine Broke Her Shaft\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12388FC2D5328B50%25402413766-1231FC2D1B831B28%25405-12D53960005CAE90%2540Afloat%252BAnd%252BAshore%252BThe%252BFulwood%252BCame%252BAround%252BThe%252BHorn%252BSafely.%252BSnake%252BRiver%252BBusiness--Oriental%252BFlour&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: Vancouver, Wash., July 24.\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 36\n| issue  = 11,486\n| date = July 25, 1896\n| page  = 6, col.2\n| editor = H.W. Scott]\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The initial plan was to have ''Undine'' taken out of service for about 10 days, during which it would replaced on its route by [[Mascot (sternwheeler)|''Mascot'']].<ref name = Shaft1896/>  This changed to keeping it in service with only one engine operating.<ref name = MNjuly28>{{Citation \n| title = Marine Notes\n| url = \n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = \n| issue  = \n| date = July 28, 1896\n| page  = 3, col\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  On July 27, 1896 ''Undine'' made the run from Vancouver to Portland with one engine in one hour and 28 minutes.<ref name = MNjuly28/>\n\n==Columbia Gorge route==\nIn March 1905 ''Undine'' was hauled out, for the first time in twelve years, at the Portland Shipbuilding Company\u2019s yard.<ref name = 1905haulout>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Hauled Out \u2014 Hull Is in Almost Perfect Condition After Twelve Years Service\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-1235F26E2E8F0D58%25402416924-1231FDA68B7E5648%254013-125BDDC5FADB3CCB%2540Buford%252BDue%252BToday%252BTransport%252BBringing%252BTwo%252BBatteries%252Bof%252BArtillery.%252BTakes%252BOut%252BThe%252BNineteenth%252BWill%252BSall&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 24\n| issue  = 12\n| date = March 19, 1905\n| page  = 14, col.3\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The hull was found to be in remarkably good condition, requiring replacement of only a few planks at the bow and the stern.<ref name = 1905haulout/>  ''Undine'' was scheduled for a thorough overall of its machinery and structure, which was expected to take about two months.<ref name = 1905haulout/>\n\nIn August 1905 ''Undine'' was employed on sightseeing trips up the Columbia River to [[Cascade Locks and Canal]].<ref name = 1905excursions>{{Citation \n| title = Scenery of Columbia \u2014 Great Up-River Trip Is Best Made on the Undine\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12383B17776F77A0%25402417062-1231FD772A62E038%254015-125D38AA01FCEE3E%2540Scenery%252BOf%252BColumbia.%252BGreat%252BUp-River%252BTrip%252BIs%252BBest%252BMade%252Bon%252Bthe%252BUndine&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 45\n| issue  = 13,933\n| date = August 4, 1905\n| page  = 16, col.1\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' departed from the Taylor Street dock at 8:30&nbsp;a.m. and returned at 6:00&nbsp;p.m.<ref name = 1905excursions/>  Round trip fare was $1.50.<ref name = 1905excursions/>\n\nOn February 11, 1906, ''Undine'' was secured by The Dalles, Portland & Astoria Navigation Company, also known as the Regulator Line, to connect with the sternwheeler [[Bailey Gatzert (sternwheeler)|''Bailey Gatzert'']] at the [[Cascades of the Columbia|Cascades]] on the route up the Columbia river to [[The Dalles, Oregon]].<ref name = ToUpperRiver>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Goes on Upper River\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-123ADDAF8CD5B888%25402417255-1231FC890E8E6508%254011-12D599A561C6F518%2540Fireboat%252BIs%252BLeaking%252BGovernment%252BInspectors%252BRecommend%252BImmediate%252BRepairs.%252BCity%252BOfficials%252BNotified%252BHall%252BNeeds%252BRecaulking%252Band&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 46\n| issue  = 14,098\n| date = February 12, 1906\n| page  = 12, col.5\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The change was made necessary by need to find a replacement for the sternwheeler [[Dalles City (sternwheeler)|''Dalles City'']], which had sunk at Curtis Landing a few days before.<ref name = ToUpperRiver/>\n\n''Dalles City'' was returned to service on March 16, 1906, after which ''Undine'' was hauled out at Portland Shipbuilding for a hull inspection.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Along the Waterfront\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-03-17/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = [[The Oregon Journal|Oregon Daily Journal]]\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 10\n| date = March 17, 1906\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor = [[Sam Jackson (publisher)|C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson]]\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' was back in service a few days later, on the Vancouver route.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Along the Waterfront\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-03-20/ed-1/seq-3/\n| newspaper = Oregon Daily Journal\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 12\n| date = March 20, 1906\n| page  = 3, col.4\n| editor = C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Funeral of Sheriff John R. Shaver==\nOn May 2, 1906, a funeral was held at the Oregon City courthouse for John R. Shaver, sheriff of [[Clackamas County, Oregon|Clackamas County]], who had been shot a few days earlier by desperado Frank Smith near [[Woodburn, Oregon]].<ref name = LastTribute>{{Citation \n| title = Hundreds Pay Last Tribute To Victim of Outlaw Smith \u2014 Business Suspended in Oregon City Out of Respect to Late Sheriff Shaver \u2014 Morbidly Curious View Body of Dead Outlaw \u2014 Jury Returns Verdict That Officer Shot Him in Performance of Duty and That Bandit Was Murderer of Three Men\n| type = Dateline: Oregon City, Or. May 2 (Special Dispatch to The Journal).\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn85042444/1906-05-02/ed-1/seq-1/\n| newspaper = Oregon Daily Journal\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 5\n| issue  = 49\n| date = May 2, 1906\n| page  = 1, col.4\n| editor = C.S. \u201cSam\u201d Jackson\n| publisher = Journal Pub. Co.\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  Although he had chosen a career in law enforcement, Shaver was a member of a [[Shaver Transportation Company|prominent steamboating family]].  At the conclusion of the funeral, ''Undine'' carried the remains to [[River View Cemetery (Portland, Oregon)|River View Cemetery]] to be interred in the Shaver family plot.<ref name = LastTribute/>\n\n==Opening of Celilo Canal==\n[[File:Undine Reynolds cartoon 1915.jpg|thumb|Cartoon published in the ''Morning Oregonian'', marking the transit of ''Undine'' from Portland to [[Lewiston, Idaho]] through the newly completed [[Celilo Canal]], May 1915]]\nWhen the [[Celilo Canal]] was opened in 1915, ''Undine'', carrying a number of dignitaries, became the first steamboat to transit the canal downstream from [[Celilo, Oregon|Celilo]] to [[Astoria, Oregon]].<ref>{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = Seattle, WA\n| chapter = Maritime Events of 1915\n| pages = 253\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}</ref>\n\nIn late April 1932, ''Undine'' was operated by the Mid-Columbia Navigation Company, which announced plans for ''Undine'' to make its first run on a route from Portland to [[The Dalles, Oregon]], arriving on at The Dalles on the night of April 26, 1932 with a cargo from Portland of sugar.<ref name = OnSchedule>{{Citation \n| title = Undine Runs on Schedule\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A00E90172CF279%25402426825-1299CDA5AC753A3A%254016-1299CDA5AC753A3A%2540%2Fhlterms%3A%2522steamer%2520Undine%2522&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Dateline: [[The Dalles, Oregon|The Dalles, Or.]], April 26 (Special).\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,299\n| date = April 27, 1932\n| page  = 17, col.8\n| editor = H.W. Scott\n| publisher = H.L. Pittock\n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  ''Undine'' would return to Portland with a new crop of wool brought in by trucks from [[Yakima, Washington]].<ref name = OnSchedule/>\n\nThe Mid-Columbia Navigation Company was organized by Thomas Larkin, president and general manager, L.N. Chambreau, traffic representative, Edward Spockerman, general manager, Robert Irish, purchasing manager, Frank Raicy, vice-president and assistant manager, C.C. Thompson, secretary and treasurer, and Harold Johnston, counsel.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Portland-The Dalles Steamer Service Inaugurated\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A009894287EEF3%25402426822-1299D022F7A96B0D%254016-12A013494B38ED8D%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| type = Photograph and caption\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 51\n| issue  = 17\n| date = April 24, 1932\n| page  = 17, cols.2\u20133\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Forced sale==\nOn July 11, 1932, crewmen who were employed on ''Undine'' during March and April of that year brought suit in the United States District Court to force the sale of the steamer and \u201cher engines, tackle, apparatus and furniture\u201d to satisfy their claims for wages.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Sale of Steamer Sought\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A0BB0E1513F476%25402426901-1299CE19CBEFF5F4%254014-12A12571350295A8%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,364\n| date = July 12, 1932\n| page  = 15, col.4\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  The case name was ''Samuel H. Shaver et al. vs. Steamer Undine''.<ref name = Motion2Sell>{{Citation \n| title = Motion Calendar Up \u2014 Federal Judge McNary to Hear Cases in Law Today\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A0C36A7B784036%25402426921-1299D2C7173121D4%25406-12A19B226CCFB42F%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 71\n| issue  = 22,381\n| date = August 1, 1932\n| page  = 7, cols.3\u20134\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>  On August 1, 1932 a motion for an order to the U.S. marshal to sell the boat was presented for hearing before U.S. district court judge [[John Hugh McNary|John H. McNary]] (1867-1936).<ref name = Motion2Sell/>  In November 1932, by order of the court, the U.S. Marshal service sold ''Undine'' to William Greenberg.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = River Vessel Bought\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A269996D6B96EA%25402427116-1299E09666B83E0C%254011-12A2B2C732BE99CB%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Sunday Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 52\n| issue  = 7\n| date = February 12, 1933\n| page  = 12, cols.2\u20133\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref>\n\n==Change of name to ''The Dalles''==\nOn October 31, 1935, the Bureau of Navigation and Steamboat Inspection, Milton A. Miller (1861-1938), Collector of Customs, announced that it had granted permission to ''Undine'', official number 221499, to change its name to ''The Dalles''.<ref>{{Citation \n| title = Miscellaneous \u2026 The Bureau of Navigation and Steamboat Inspection \u2026\n| url = http://proxy.multcolib.org:2084/resources/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_dat=document_id%3Aimage%252Fv2%253A11A73E5827618330%2540EANX-NB-12A507BEB6E513F1%25402428107-12A072ADF40BD345%254010-12A5D1276D3B8338%2540&rft_id=info%3Asid%2Finfoweb.newsbank.com&rft_val_format=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Actx&svc_dat=AMNEWS&req_dat=0D10F2CADB4B24C0\n| newspaper = Morning Oregonian\n| location = Portland, OR\n| volume = 74\n| issue  = 23,398\n| date = October 31, 1935\n| page  = 11, col.11\n| editor = \n| publisher = \n| nopp = yes}}</ref><ref>{{Find a Grave \n| id = 29385157\n| name = Milton Armington Miller\n| accessdate = July 23, 2017\n }}</ref>\n\n==Disposition==\n''The Dalles'' (ex ''Undine'') was scrapped in 1940.<ref>{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| chapter = \n| pages = 484\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Commons category|Undine (sternwheeler)}}\n\n=== Printed sources===\n* <!-- AFFLECK, CENTURY OF PADDLEWHEELERS -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Affleck \n| author1-first = Edward L. \n| title = A Century of Paddlewheelers in the Pacific Northwest, the Yukon, and Alaska \n| chapter =\n| lccn = \n| isbn =0-920034-08-X \n| location = Vancouver, BC \n| publisher =  Alexander Nicholls Press \n| date = 2000 \n| at = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- MILLS, STERNWHEELERS UP COLUMBIA -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Mills \n| author1-first = Randall V. \n| author-link1 = Randall V. Mills \n| title = Sternwheelers up Columbia -- A Century of Steamboating in the Oregon Country | isbn = 0-8032-5874-7 \n| chapter =\n| lccn = 77007161 \n| location =  Lincoln NE \n| publisher = University of Nebraska \n| date = 1947 \n| pages = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- NEWELL, ed. H.W. McCURDY MARINE HISTORY -->{{Cite book \n| editor1-last = Newell \n| editor1-first = Gordon R. \n| title = H.W. McCurdy Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| publisher = Superior Pub. Co\n| date = 1966  \n| location = [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle, WA]]\n| chapter = \n| pages = 253, 308, 324, 484, 567\n| oclc =\n| lccn =66025424\n| nopp = yes \n}}\n* <!-- TIMMEN, BLOW FOR THE LANDING -->{{cite book \n| author1-last = Timmen \n| author1-first = Fritz\n| title = Blow for the Landing -- A Hundred Years of Steam Navigation on the Waters of the West \n| isbn = 0-87004-221-1 \n| lccn = 73150815 \n| location =  Caldwell, ID \n| publisher =  [[Caxton Press (United States)|Caxton Printers]] \n| date = 1973 \n| pages = \n| nopp = yes}}\n* <!-- WRIGHT, ed. LEWIS AND DRYDEN MARINE HISTORY -->{{cite book\n| editor1-last = Wright \n| editor1-first = E.W. \n| title = Lewis & Dryden's Marine History of the Pacific Northwest \n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=seRDAAAAYAAJ \n| chapter = \n| chapter-url = \n| lccn = 28001147 \n| location = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland, OR]] \n| publisher = Lewis and Dryden Printing Co. \n| date = 1895 \n| page = \n| nopp = yes}}\n\n=== On-line newspapers and journals ===\n* <!-- HISTORIC OREGON NEWSPAPERS-->{{cite web\n| url = http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu\n| title = Historic Oregon Newspapers\n| publisher = [[University of Oregon]]\n| accessdate = \n}}\n* <!-- CHRONICLING AMERICA (LoC)-->{{cite web\n| url  = http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov\n| title = Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers\n| publisher = [[Library of Congress]]\n| accessdate = \n}}\n\n{{Steamboats Pacific Northwest}}\n\n[[Category:Paddle steamers]]\n[[Category:Steamboats of the Columbia River]]\n[[Category:1867 ships]]\n[[Category:Steamboats of Oregon]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Mtsmallwood", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix red link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undine_(Columbia_River_sternwheeler)"}
{"title_page": "Xia Ruifang", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Xia (surname)|Xia]]}}\n\n'''Xia Ruifang''' ({{zh|\u590f\u745e\u82b3}}; 1871{{spaced ndash}}10 January 1941) was a Chinese publisher who co-founded the [[Commercial Press]] in 1897 and was its director until his assassination by [[Chen Qimei]] in 1941.\n\n==Early life==\nXia Ruifang was born in 1871 in [[Qingpu District]] near [[Shanghai]]. His mother was a ''baomu'' (part-nurse, part-maid) who worked for the family of John Marshall Willoughby Farnham.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=189}} At age 11, Xia and his mother moved to Shanghai and attended the Presbyterian Qingxin Hall school, which Farnham was the director of. At Qingxin, Xia learnt printing and interned at the American Presbyterian Mission Press. Graduating in 1889, he found employment as a typesetter at the Chinese-language ''Wenhui bao'' and subsequently the English-language ''North China Herald''.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=189}}\n\n==Career==\nUnhappy with his treatment at the ''Herald'', Xia decided to found his own publishing firm with the help of Qingxin schoolmates Bao Xianen, Bao Xianchang, and Gao Fengchi.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=190}} Their first project, a Chinese translation of an English textbook, sold some three thousand copies. Spurred by the success of their maiden venture, the four partners quickly invested in printers from [[Japan]] and established their headquarters at a three-room shop near Jiangxi Lane; the Baos' sisters christened the start-up ''Shangwu yinshu guan'' or [[The Commercial Press]].{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=190}} In 1898, the company acquired the Japanese printshop ''Xiuwen yinshuaju'' and relocated to larger premises, this time a twelve-room building along Shunqing Lane in Beijing Road. Xia was credited with being the \"brains\" of the group who secured funding while the Baos did the actual printing; Gao continued working for the American Presbyterian Mission Press. In 1902, a fire destroyed most of the equipment that the Press had inherited from ''Xiuwen'', although the company was still able to publish five new volumes of its English-Chinese textbook.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=191}}\n\nAs the company was short on manpower, Xia had to juggle many roles, including editor, manager, proofreader, and accountant; he even personally went down to the firm's paper supplier in [[Pudong]] to collect paper. With a monthly salary of twenty-four ''[[yuan]]'', Xia had to sell insurance for a side income. Following a series of botched translation projects, Xia was faced with a cash flow problem; he was advised by his writer friend Bao Tianxiao to establish a proper editorial office and invite new partners to better manage the business.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=195}} In 1901, Xia managed to convince the [[Hanlin Academy|Hanlin]] scholar Zhang Yuanji to invest in his company; Sheng in turn recruited a partner and the company, now renamed to ''Shangwu yinshu guan gufen youxian gongsi'' or Commercial Press, Limited, saw its capital rise from 3,750 to 50,000 ''yuan''.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=195\u2013196}}\n\nNow able to publish his own books, Xia moved to a retail space in Henan Road and purchased a building on Fujian North Road that he converted into a workshop. The Commercial Press' first editorial office was established in Tangjia Lane and staffed by some four or five persons personally recommended by Zhang, with the philosopher [[Cai Yuanpei]] serving as supervising editor.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}} Seeing it as a chance to improve the country's educational system, Cai handpicked educators from Nanyang Public Institute (now [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]]), including Jiang Weiqiao and Wu Danchu to edit textbooks on a diverse list of topics including Chinese literature, history, and geography.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}} With the introduction of Zhang Yuanji and associates, there were now two camps in the company: the \"Church Band\" led by the Bao brothers and comprising [[Ningbo]] Presbyterians, and the \"Scholars' School\" led by Zhang and comprising intellectuals from [[Fujian]], [[Jiangsu]], and [[Zhejiang]]. Xia identified with the former group but ensured that there would be no conflict between the two.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}}\n\nHowever, in 1902, the company's textbook projects came to a standstill after Cai Yuanpei fled to [[Qingdao]] to avoid prosecution for sedition; Zhang took over as supervising editor a year later and enacted sweeping changes that allowed the firm to fend off competitors like Kkinkodo, Wenming, and Nanyang. The textbook collection envisaged by Cai finally came to fruition in 1904 after a series of major overhauls and a record-breaking few hundred thousand copies were sold in a few months, thus establishing the Commercial Press as the unrivalled leader in the Chinese publication industry.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=196\u2013198}} They would continue to \"utterly dominate\" the textbook market in China, which had previously been largely untapped, until around 1911.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=196\u2013199}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Christopher|last=Reed|title=Gutenberg in Shanghai: Chinese Print Capitalism, 1876-1937|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xabu9_VII18C|year=2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-4121-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xia, Ruifang}}\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Chinese people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Xia (surname)|Xia]]}}\n\n'''Xia Ruifang''' ({{zh|\u590f\u745e\u82b3}}; 1871{{spaced ndash}}10 January 1941) was a Chinese publisher who co-founded the [[Commercial Press]] in 1897 and was its director until his assassination by [[Chen Qimei]] in 1941.\n\n==Early life==\nXia Ruifang was born in 1871 in [[Qingpu District]] near [[Shanghai]]. His mother was a ''baomu'' (part-nurse, part-maid) who worked for the family of John Marshall Willoughby Farnham.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=189}} At age 11, Xia and his mother moved to Shanghai and attended the Presbyterian Qingxin Hall school, which Farnham was the director of. At Qingxin, Xia learnt printing and interned at the American Presbyterian Mission Press. Graduating in 1889, he found employment as a typesetter at the Chinese-language ''Wenhui bao'' and subsequently the English-language ''North China Herald''.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=189}} \n\n==Career==\nUnhappy with his treatment at the ''Herald'', Xia decided to found his own publishing firm with the help of Qingxin schoolmates Bao Xianen, Bao Xianchang, and Gao Fengchi.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=190}} Their first project, a Chinese translation of an English textbook, sold some three thousand copies. Spurred by the success of their maiden venture, the four partners quickly invested in printers from [[Japan]] and established their headquarters at a three-room shop near Jiangxi Lane; the Baos' sisters christened the start-up ''Shangwu yinshu guan'' or [[The Commercial Press]].{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=190}} In 1898, the company acquired the Japanese printshop ''Xiuwen yinshuaju'' and relocated to larger premises, this time a twelve-room building along Shunqing Lane in Beijing Road. Xia was credited with being the \"brains\" of the group who secured funding while the Baos did the actual printing; Gao continued working for the American Presbyterian Mission Press. In 1902, a fire destroyed most of the equipment that the Press had inherited from ''Xiuwen'', although the company was still able to publish five new volumes of its English-Chinese textbook.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=191}}\n\nAs the company was short on manpower, Xia had to juggle many roles, including editor, manager, proofreader, and accountant; he even personally went down to the firm's paper supplier in [[Pudong]] to collect paper. With a monthly salary of twenty-four ''[[yuan]]'', Xia had to sell insurance for a side income. Following a series of botched translation projects, Xia was faced with a cash flow problem; he was advised by his writer friend Bao Tianxiao to establish a proper editorial office and invite new partners to better manage the business.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=195}} In 1901, Xia managed to convince the [[Hanlin Academy|Hanlin]] scholar Zhang Yuanji to invest in his company; Sheng in turn recruited a partner and the company, now renamed to ''Shangwu yinshu guan gufen youxian gongsi'' or Commercial Press, Limited, saw its capital rise from 3,750 to 50,000 ''yuan''.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=195\u2013196}} \n\nNow able to publish his own books, Xia moved to a retail space in Henan Road and purchased a building on Fujian North Road that he converted into a workshop. The Commerical Press' first editorial office was established in Tangjia Lane and staffed by some four or five persons personally recommended by Zhang, with the philosopher [[Cai Yuanpei]] serving as supervising editor.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}} Seeing it as a chance to improve the country's educational system, Cai handpicked educators from Nanyang Public Institute (now [[Shanghai Jiao Tong University]]), including Jiang Weiqiao and Wu Danchu to edit textbooks on a diverse list of topics including Chinese literature, history, and geography.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}} With the introduction of Zhang Yuanji and associates, there were now two camps in the company: the \"Church Band\" led by the Bao brothers and comprising [[Ningbo]] Presbyterians, and the \"Scholars' School\" led by Zhang and comprising intellectuals from [[Fujian]], [[Jiangsu]], and [[Zhejiang]]. Xia identified with the former group but ensured that there would be no conflict between the two.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|p=196}} \n\nHowever, in 1902, the company's textbook projects came to a standstill after Cai Yuanpei fled to [[Qingdao]] to avoid prosecution for sedition; Zhang took over as supervising editor a year later and enacted sweeping changes that allowed the firm to fend off competitors like Kkinkodo, Wenming, and Nanyang. The textbook collection envisaged by Cai finally came to fruition in 1904 after a series of major overhauls and a record-breaking few hundred thousand copies were sold in a few months, thus establishing the Commercial Press as the unrivalled leader in the Chinese publication industry.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=196\u2013198}} They would continue to \"utterly dominate\" the textbook market in China, which had previously been largely untapped, until around 1911.{{Sfn|Reed|2011|pp=196\u2013199}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|ref=harv|first=Christopher|last=Reed|title=Gutenberg in Shanghai: Chinese Print Capitalism, 1876-1937|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xabu9_VII18C|year=2011|publisher=UBC Press|isbn=978-0-7748-4121-4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xia, Ruifang}}\n\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Chinese people]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Commerical \u2192 Commercial", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xia_Ruifang"}
{"title_page": "Redthroat", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Redthroat\n| image = The birds of Australia (16989832911).jpg\n| image_caption = Redthroat at top.\n| genus = Pyrrholaemus\n| species = brunneus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1841\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704593A93976763 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704593A93976763.en }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''redthroat''' (''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'') is a small, mostly ground-dwelling species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Australia, occurring mostly in arid and semi-arid areas containing [[acacia]] and [[Chenopodiaceae|chenopod]] shrublands. The species has a distinctive red throat patch and is able to mimic the calls of numerous other bird species.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe first [[Species description|formal description]] of the redthroat was by the English ornithologist and bird artist, [[John Gould]], in 1841 under the present [[binomial name]] ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1840 | title=''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=Part 8 | page=173 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30571612 }} Although bearing the year 1840 on the title page, the volume did not appear until 1841.</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=426 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484127 }}</ref> The name of the genus ''Pyrrholaemus'' is from classical Greek ''{{lang|grc-Latn|pyrrhos}}'' meaning 'flame-coloured' or 'red' and ''{{lang|grc-Latn|laimos}}'' for 'throat'. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''{{lang|la|brunneus}}'' is [[New Latin|modern Latin]] for 'brown'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n79 79], 326 }}</ref> The redthroat is a small [[passerine]] bird within the family [[Acanthizidae]], also known as the Australasian warblers. The Acanthizidae were once regarded as a subfamily within the family [[Pardalote|Pardalotidae]]; although current revisions place the Acanthizidae in their own family, sister to the Pardalotidae.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The taxonomy and species of birds of Australia and its territories|last=Christidas |first=Les|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|year=1994 |isbn=1875122060 |location=|pages=|oclc= 635775426}}</ref> The species most closely related to the redthroat are the [[speckled warbler]] (''Chthonicola sagittata''), which was previously classified in the same genus as the redthroat (''Pyrrholaemus''), and the [[pilotbird]] (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'').<ref name=Gardner>{{Cite journal|last=Gardner |first=Janet|last2=Trueman |first2=John|date=2010 |title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|url= https://publications.csiro.au/rpr/download?pid=csiro:EP10371&dsid=DS2|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=55 |issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi= 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref> Recent phylogenetic studies have found that this clade of species (''Pyrrholaemus-Chthonicola-Pyncnoptilus'') is sister to the [[Hylacola|heathwrens]] and [[Calamanthus|fieldwrens]] (''Hylacola-Calamanthus'').<ref name=Gardner/>\n\n== Description ==\nA small {{cvt|11|-|12|cm}} shy greyish-brown bird, the redthroat is most often seen swiftly darting through low branches and shrubs or hopping mouse-like on the ground. Only adult males have the distinctive small, rusty-brown throat patch, which gives the species its common name and the absence of which makes the identification of females and juveniles more difficult. The upper part of the head, body, wings, and tail are a dark brownish-grey, particularly dark on the rump and tail. While the underbody is predominantly whitish-grey, with a more whitish belly and pale buff colour blending into the flanks and undertail-coverts. The tail has prominent white patches on the tips of the outer feathers, which can be seen during flight and with the tail folded. Fine off-white scalloping is visible on the forehead, with off-white eye rings and lores merging into the lighter underparts of the body. It may be confused with some [[Acanthiza|thornbill]] species, which are more compact with a shorter tail than the redthroat. It is unlikely to be mistaken for fieldwrens or heathwrens, which have a more strongly upturned tail at rest.<ref name=HANZAB>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic birds. Volume 6: Pardalotes to shrike-thrushes|last=Higgins |first=PJ|last2=Peter |first2=JM |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne |pages= |oclc= 772731860}}</ref>\n\nThe melodious call, similar to that of a canary, has sustained warbling and loud cheery notes.<ref name=HANZAB/> In addition to its own calls, the redthroat is able to [[Mimicry|mimic]] the calls of numerous other birds, including the [[pied butcherbird]], [[rufous fieldwren]], [[grey fantail]], [[fairywren]]s, and thornbills. The redthroat has even been known to mimic the non-vocal sound of whistling wingbeats made by a [[crested pigeon]] in flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Pyrrholaemus-brunneus|title=Redthroat (Pyrrholaemus brunneus) :: xeno-canto|website=www.xeno-canto.org|access-date=2017-06-15}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/> Although both sexes call throughout the year, during the breeding season male calls are more sustained. The species is vocal when foraging and will also sing while perched atop shrubs and taller trees.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe redthroat is endemic to mainland Australia, occurring in all states and territories, except the [[Australian Capital Territory]] and [[Tasmania]]. The species is most prevalent in Western Australia and South Australia. It has a widespread but scattered distribution throughout most of South Australia. In Western Australia, the species is not present in the far north or the south-east, but is prevalent throughout the mid-latitudes of the state. In the Northern Territory, the species is restricted to the south of the state, around the [[Simpson Desert]] and the [[MacDonnell Ranges]]. In Queensland, the species is restricted to inland south-western regions. In Victoria, the species is restricted to the [[Mallee (Victoria)|mallee]] regions in the northwest of the state.<ref name=HANZAB/> In New South Wales, the species is only known to occur in the far west, in several core populations, including Broken Hill, Tibooburra, Penarie and Nearie Lake Nature Reserve.<ref name=NSWOEH>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedSpeciesApp/profile.aspx?id=10721|title=Redthroat - profile|last=|first= |date=|website=NSW Government, Office of Environment and Heritage|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe species is thought to be mostly sedentary, with no evidence to suggest seasonal migration. Individuals recaptured after banding have all been found within {{convert|10|km|miles|2}} of the banding site.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Habitat ==\nThe habitat of the redthroat consists primarily of arid and semi-arid regions of inland Australia, but it also occupies some coastal areas, as well as plains and rangelands. Communities it favours are most often acacia and chenopod shrublands. These communities are usually characterised by an overstory of mulga (''[[Acacia aneura]]''), red mulga (''[[Acacia cyperophylla|A. cyperophylla]]'') or lacewood (''A. shirleyi'') with an understory of saltbush (''[[Atriplex]] sp''.), bluebush (''[[Chenopodium]] sp.)'' or emu bush (''[[Eremophila (plant)|Eremophila]] sp.)''.<ref name=HANZAB/> However, in some areas the species is known to occur in [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] with a diverse understory, semi-arid woodlands, [[banksia]] and [[Leptospermum|tea tree]] thickets and shrublands with an overstory of [[Callitris glaucophylla|white cypress]].<ref name=NSWOEH/> The consistent feature among these habitats appears to be the presence of a complex understory which provides suitable foraging and nesting resources for this shy, mostly ground-dwelling species.\n\n== Diet and foraging behaviour ==\nRedthroats are [[omnivore]]s with a diet consisting of seeds from grasses and shrubs as well as a broad variety of invertebrates such as spiders, molluscs and insects.<ref name=HANZAB/> Observations of redthroat foraging behaviour found that the species predominantly forages at heights of less than 1m (73% of observations) and was not observed foraging at heights greater than 3m.<ref name=Morris>{{Cite journal|last=Morris|first=WJ|last2=Wooler|first2=RD|date=2001|title=The structure and dynamics of an assemblage of small birds in a semi-arid eucalypt woodland in south-western Australia|journal=Emu |volume=101 |pages=7\u201312 |doi=10.1071/MU00062}}</ref> This study found that redthroats feed mostly by pouncing on prey from the ground or [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] in low vegetation, with very few instances of hunting on the wing.<ref name=Morris /> Another study of foraging behaviour found that all observations of foraging occurred on the ground (<0.1 m), using a combination of gleaning and probing.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Recher |first=HF|last2=Davis |first2=WD |date=2002 |title=Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia|url= http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85(2)/recher85(2).pdf |journal= Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia |volume=85 |pages=103\u2013111}}</ref>\n\n== Breeding and nesting ==\nBreeding mostly occurs between June\u2013December with some geographic variation in timing. Little is known about sexual behaviour, although the species appears to breed in pairs. Nests are relatively large for a bird of its size (9\u201314&nbsp;cm), often domed, spherical or domed with a round entrance near the top (2.5\u20134&nbsp;cm). Usually constructed of bark strips and bark fibre, often lined with feathers, fur or soft plant material. Nests are located on or close to the ground among shrubs, grass tussocks, at the base of trees, in fallen logs or in small depressions. Two to four eggs are laid and the female is solely responsible for incubating the eggs. The redthroat and the closely related speckled warbler are the only members of the acanthizids which have a solid coloured chocolate brown egg.<ref name=Gardner/> Furthermore, the redthroat (and the speckled warbler) are the primary host species of some [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[black-eared cuckoo]] (''Chrysococcyx osculans'')and [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'') which remove redthroat eggs from the nest and lay their own similar looking eggs.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhhRGJNqQhIC&pg=PA244 |title=The Avian Brood Parasites: Deception at the Nest|last=Johnsgard |first=Paul A.|date=1997-11-06 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195354997 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n==Conservation status==\nPopulations of redthroats have declined in many areas throughout Australia and the species is subject to many threatening processes. This has warranted its conservation listing in New South Wales and Victoria as follows:\n* The redthroat is listed as '''threatened''' on the Victorian [[Flora and Fauna Guarantee Act (1988)]].<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050718182613/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB |date=2005-07-18 }}</ref>  Under this Act, an ''Action Statement'' for the recovery and future management of this species has not yet been prepared.<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911130015/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n* On the 2013 advisory list of threatened vertebrate fauna in Victoria, the redthroat is listed as [[endangered]].<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book|title=Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2013|publisher=Department of Sustainability and Environment|year=2013 |isbn=978-1-74287-504-0 |location=East Melbourne, Victoria|page=11 |author=Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment|url= https://www.environment.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0014/50450/Advisory-List-of-Threatened-Vertebrate-Fauna_FINAL-2013.pdf}}</ref>\n* The redthroat is listed at Vulnerable under the NSW Threatened Species Conservation Act (1995)<ref name=NSWOEH/>\nIn New South Wales, several threatening processes affecting redthroat populations have been formally identified, including the following: \n* Clearing of suitable vegetation communities can cause range contractions and isolate populations.\n* [[Overgrazing]] by feral herbivores particularly goats can cause habitat degradation and prevents habitat regeneration for the species. \n* The infestation of suitable habitat by the noxious environmental weed [[Mesquite]] also impacts habitat values and foraging resources.\n* Given that redthroats are predominantly ground-dwelling and nesting birds, they are also highly susceptible to predation by exotic predators such as [[fox]]es and [[cat]]s. \nAlthough the species is not yet federally listed under the [[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]], the threatening processes listed above are present throughout most of the species distribution. The ongoing impacts of land clearing, noxious weeds, introduced herbivore and introduced predators are likely to cause further declines throughout the species range, which may warrant further environmental protection measures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1310023}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrrholaemus]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1841]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Redthroat\n| image = The birds of Australia (16989832911).jpg\n| image_caption = Redthroat at top.\n| genus = Pyrrholaemus\n| species = brunneus\n| authority = [[John Gould|Gould]], 1841\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=IUCN>{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704593A93976763 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704593A93976763.en }}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''redthroat''' (''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'') is a small, mostly ground-dwelling species of [[bird]] in the family [[Acanthizidae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Australia, occurring mostly in arid and semi-arid areas containing [[acacia]] and [[Chenopodiaceae|chenopod]] shrublands. The species has a distinctive red throat patch and is able to mimic the calls of numerous other bird species.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe first [[Species description|formal description]] of the redthroat was by the English ornithologist and bird artist, [[John Gould]], in 1841 under the present [[binomial name]] ''Pyrrholaemus brunneus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1840 | title=''Pyrrholaemus brunneus'' | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=Part 8 | page=173 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/30571612 }} Although bearing the year 1840 on the title page, the volume did not appear until 1841.</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr | editor2-last=Cottrell | editor2-first=G. William | year=1986 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=Volume 11 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=426 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14484127 }}</ref> The name of the genus ''Pyrrholaemus'' is from classical Greek ''{{lang|grc-Latn|pyrrhos}}'' meaning 'flame-coloured' or 'red' and ''{{lang|grc-Latn|laimos}}'' for 'throat'. The [[Specific name (zoology)|specific epithet]] ''{{lang|la|brunneus}}'' is [[New Latin|modern Latin]] for 'brown'.<ref name=Helm>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title= The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | url=https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn= 978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling/page/n79 79], 326 }}</ref> The redthroat is a small [[passerine]] bird within the family [[Acanthizidae]], also known as the Australasian warblers. The Acanthizidae were once regarded as a subfamily within the family [[Pardalote|Pardalotidae]]; although current revisions place the Acanthizidae in their own family, sister to the Pardalotidae.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The taxonomy and species of birds of Australia and its territories|last=Christidas |first=Les|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|year=1994 |isbn=1875122060 |location=|pages=|oclc= 635775426}}</ref> The species most closely related to the redthroat are the [[speckled warbler]] (''Chthonicola sagittata''), which was previously classified in the same genus as the redthroat (''Pyrrholaemus''), and the [[pilotbird]] (''Pycnoptilus floccosus'').<ref name=Gardner>{{Cite journal|last=Gardner |first=Janet|last2=Trueman |first2=John|date=2010 |title=Phylogeny and evolution of the Meliphagoidea, the largest radiation of Australasian songbirds|url= https://publications.csiro.au/rpr/download?pid=csiro:EP10371&dsid=DS2|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|volume=55 |issue=3|pages=1087\u20131102|doi= 10.1016/j.ympev.2010.02.005|pmid=20152917}}</ref> Recent phylogenetic studies have found that this clade of species (''Pyrrholaemus-Chthonicola-Pyncnoptilus'') is sister to the [[Hylacola|heathwrens]] and [[Calamanthus|fieldwrens]] (''Hylacola-Calamanthus'').<ref name=Gardner/>\n\n== Description ==\nA small {{cvt|11|-|12|cm}} shy greyish-brown bird, the redthroat is most often seen swiftly darting through low branches and shrubs or hopping mouse-like on the ground. Only adult males have the distinctive small, rusty-brown throat patch, which gives the species its common name and the absence of which makes the identification of females and juveniles more difficult. The upper part of the head, body, wings, and tail are a dark brownish-grey, particularly dark on the rump and tail. While the underbody is predominantly whitish-grey, with a more whitish belly and pale buff colour blending into the flanks and undertail-coverts. The tail has prominent white patches on the tips of the outer feathers, which can be seen during flight and with the tail folded. Fine off-white scalloping is visible on the forehead, with off-white eye rings and lores merging into the lighter underparts of the body. It may be confused with some [[Acanthiza|thornbill]] species, which are more compact with a shorter tail than the redthroat. It is unlikely to be mistaken for fieldwrens or heathwrens, which have a more strongly upturned tail at rest.<ref name=HANZAB>{{Cite book|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic birds. Volume 6: Pardalotes to shrike-thrushes|last=Higgins |first=PJ|last2=Peter |first2=JM |publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2002|isbn=0-19-553244-9|location=Melbourne |pages= |oclc= 772731860}}</ref>\n\nThe melodious call, similar to that of a canary, has sustained warbling and loud cheery notes.<ref name=HANZAB/> In addition to its own calls, the redthroat is able to [[Mimicry|mimic]] the calls of numerous other birds, including the [[pied butcherbird]], [[rufous fieldwren]], [[grey fantail]], [[fairywren]]s, and thornbills. The redthroat has even been known to mimic the non-vocal sound of whistling wingbeats made by a [[crested pigeon]] in flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Pyrrholaemus-brunneus|title=Redthroat (Pyrrholaemus brunneus) :: xeno-canto|website=www.xeno-canto.org|access-date=2017-06-15}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/> Although both sexes call throughout the year, during the breeding season male calls are more sustained. The species is vocal when foraging and will also sing while perched atop shrubs and taller trees.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Distribution ==\nThe redthroat is endemic to mainland Australia, occurring in all states and territories, except the [[Australian Capital Territory]] and [[Tasmania]]. The species is most prevalent in Western Australia and South Australia. It has a widespread but scattered distribution throughout most of South Australia. In Western Australia, the species is not present in the far north or the south-east, but is prevalent throughout the mid-latitudes of the state. In the Northern Territory, the species is restricted to the south of the state, around the [[Simpson Desert]] and the [[MacDonnell Ranges]]. In Queensland, the species is restricted to inland south-western regions. In Victoria, the species is restricted to the [[mallee]] regions in the north west of the state.<ref name=HANZAB/> In New South Wales, the species is only known to occur in the far west, in several core populations, including Broken Hill, Tibooburra, Penarie and Nearie Lake Nature Reserve.<ref name=NSWOEH>{{Cite web|url=http://www.environment.nsw.gov.au/threatenedSpeciesApp/profile.aspx?id=10721|title=Redthroat - profile|last=|first= |date=|website=NSW Government, Office of Environment and Heritage|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe species is thought to be mostly sedentary, with no evidence to suggest seasonal migration. Individuals recaptured after banding have all been found within {{convert|10|km|miles|2}} of the banding site.<ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n== Habitat ==\nThe habitat of the redthroat consists primarily of arid and semi-arid regions of inland Australia, but it also occupies some coastal areas, as well as plains and rangelands. Communities it favours are most often acacia and chenopod shrublands. These communities are usually characterised by an overstory of mulga (''[[Acacia aneura]]''), red mulga (''[[Acacia cyperophylla|A. cyperophylla]]'') or lacewood (''A. shirleyi'') with an understory of saltbush (''[[Atriplex]] sp''.), bluebush (''[[Chenopodium]] sp.)'' or emu bush (''[[Eremophila (plant)|Eremophila]] sp.)''.<ref name=HANZAB/> However, in some areas the species is known to occur in [[Mallee (habit)|mallee]] with a diverse understory, semi-arid woodlands, [[banksia]] and [[Leptospermum|tea tree]] thickets and shrublands with an overstory of [[Callitris glaucophylla|white cypress]].<ref name=NSWOEH/> The consistent feature among these habitats appears to be the presence of a complex understory which provides suitable foraging and nesting resources for this shy, mostly ground-dwelling species.\n\n== Diet and foraging behaviour ==\nRedthroats are [[omnivore]]s with a diet consisting of seeds from grasses and shrubs as well as a broad variety of invertebrates such as spiders, molluscs and insects.<ref name=HANZAB/> Observations of redthroat foraging behaviour found that the species predominantly forages at heights of less than 1m (73% of observations) and was not observed foraging at heights greater than 3m.<ref name=Morris>{{Cite journal|last=Morris|first=WJ|last2=Wooler|first2=RD|date=2001|title=The structure and dynamics of an assemblage of small birds in a semi-arid eucalypt woodland in south-western Australia|journal=Emu |volume=101 |pages=7\u201312 |doi=10.1071/MU00062}}</ref> This study found that redthroats feed mostly by pouncing on prey from the ground or [[Gleaning (birds)|gleaning]] in low vegetation, with very few instances of hunting on the wing.<ref name=Morris /> Another study of foraging behaviour found that all observations of foraging occurred on the ground (<0.1 m), using a combination of gleaning and probing.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Recher |first=HF|last2=Davis |first2=WD |date=2002 |title=Foraging profile of a Salmon Gum woodland avifauna in Western Australia|url= http://www.rswa.org.au/publications/Journal/85(2)/recher85(2).pdf |journal= Journal of the Royal Society of Western Australia |volume=85 |pages=103\u2013111}}</ref>\n\n== Breeding and nesting ==\nBreeding mostly occurs between June\u2013December with some geographic variation in timing. Little is known about sexual behaviour, although the species appears to breed in pairs. Nests are relatively large for a bird of its size (9\u201314&nbsp;cm), often domed, spherical or domed with a round entrance near the top (2.5\u20134&nbsp;cm). Usually constructed of bark strips and bark fibre, often lined with feathers, fur or soft plant material. Nests are located on or close to the ground among shrubs, grass tussocks, at the base of trees, in fallen logs or in small depressions. Two to four eggs are laid and the female is solely responsible for incubating the eggs. The redthroat and the closely related speckled warbler are the only members of the acanthizids which have a solid coloured chocolate brown egg.<ref name=Gardner/> Furthermore, the redthroat (and the speckled warbler) are the primary host species of some [[brood parasite]]s such as the [[black-eared cuckoo]] (''Chrysococcyx osculans'')and [[fan-tailed cuckoo]] (''Cacomantis flabelliformis'') which remove redthroat eggs from the nest and lay their own similar looking eggs.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=hhhRGJNqQhIC&pg=PA244 |title=The Avian Brood Parasites: Deception at the Nest|last=Johnsgard |first=Paul A.|date=1997-11-06 |publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780195354997 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=HANZAB/>\n\n==Conservation status==\nPopulations of redthroats have declined in many areas throughout Australia and the species is subject to many threatening processes. This has warranted its conservation listing in New South Wales and Victoria as follows:\n* The redthroat is listed as '''threatened''' on the Victorian [[Flora and Fauna Guarantee Act (1988)]].<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050718182613/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/EADA0F1874AF9CF24A2567C1001020A388BBA5581CF9D859CA256BB300271BDB |date=2005-07-18 }}</ref>  Under this Act, an ''Action Statement'' for the recovery and future management of this species has not yet been prepared.<ref>[http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 Department of Sustainability and Environment, Victoria] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060911130015/http://www.dse.vic.gov.au/DSE/nrenpa.nsf/LinkView/617768308BCB666E4A25684E00192281E7A24BB36FF60A144A256DEA00244294 |date=2006-09-11 }}</ref>\n* On the 2013 advisory list of threatened vertebrate fauna in Victoria, the redthroat is listed as [[endangered]].<ref name=\"DSE200\">{{cite book|title=Advisory List of Threatened Vertebrate Fauna in Victoria - 2013|publisher=Department of Sustainability and Environment|year=2013 |isbn=978-1-74287-504-0 |location=East Melbourne, Victoria|page=11 |author=Victorian Department of Sustainability and Environment|url= https://www.environment.vic.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0014/50450/Advisory-List-of-Threatened-Vertebrate-Fauna_FINAL-2013.pdf}}</ref>\n* The redthroat is listed at Vulnerable under the NSW Threatened Species Conservation Act (1995)<ref name=NSWOEH/>\nIn New South Wales, several threatening processes affecting redthroat populations have been formally identified, including the following: \n* Clearing of suitable vegetation communities can cause range contractions and isolate populations.\n* [[Overgrazing]] by feral herbivores particularly goats can cause habitat degradation and prevents habitat regeneration for the species. \n* The infestation of suitable habitat by the noxious environmental weed [[Mesquite]] also impacts habitat values and foraging resources.\n* Given that redthroats are predominantly ground-dwelling and nesting birds, they are also highly susceptible to predation by exotic predators such as [[fox]]es and [[cat]]s. \nAlthough the species is not yet federally listed under the [[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]], the threatening processes listed above are present throughout most of the species distribution. The ongoing impacts of land clearing, noxious weeds, introduced herbivore and introduced predators are likely to cause further declines throughout the species range, which may warrant further environmental protection measures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n* Del Hoyo, J.; Elliot, A. & Christie D. (editors). (2006). Handbook of the Birds of the World. Volume 12: Picathartes to Tits and Chickadees. Lynx Edicions. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-42-2}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q1310023}}\n\n[[Category:Pyrrholaemus]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1841]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Redthroat"}
